# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: greece
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:greece/1000000000-number] In standard form, it is written as **1 × 109**.
[src:greece/1000000000-number] The metric prefix giga indicates 1,000,000,000 times the base unit.
[src:greece/1000000000-number] One billion years may be called an *eon* in astronomy or geology.
[src:greece/1000000000-number] Previously in British English (but not in American English), the word "billion" referred exclusively to a million millions (1,000,000,000,000).
[src:greece/1000000000-number] However, this is not common anymore, and the word has been used to mean one thousand million (1,000,000,000) for several decades.
[src:greece/1000000000-number] The term ***milliard*** could also be used to refer to 1,000,000,000; whereas "milliard" is rarely used in English, variations on this name often appear in other languages.
[src:greece/1000000000-number] In the Indian numbering system, it is known as 100 crore or 1 arab.
[src:greece/1000000000-number] It is a common metric used in macroeconomics when describing national economies.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] The 1896 Summer Olympics, officially known as the Games of the I Olympiad, were a summer multi-sport event held in Athens, the capital of Greece, from 6 to 15 April 1896, and were the first Olympic Games of the Modern era.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] A total of 241 athletes from 14 nations participated in 43 events in nine sports at these games.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] Ten of the fourteen participating nations earned medals, and three medals were won by mixed teams, i.e., teams made up of athletes from multiple nations.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] The United States won the most gold medals (11) with 14 athletes participating.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] In contrast, the host nation, Greece, with 169 athletes participating, won the most medals overall (47) as well as the most silver (18) and bronze (19) medals, finishing with one less gold medal than the United States, having 155 athletes more than the U.S.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] In the early Olympic Games, several team events were contested by athletes from multiple nations.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] Retroactively, the IOC created the designation "Mixed team" (with the country code ZZX) to refer to this group of athletes.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] Some athletes won medals individually and as part of a mixed team, so these medals are tabulated under different nations in the official counts.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] Dionysios Kasdaglis, an athlete of Greek origins living in Alexandria, Egypt, is listed by the IOC as Greek during both his competition in the singles tennis competition and the doubles tennis competition along with his teammate, the Greek athlete Demetrios Petrokokkinos.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] During these inaugural Olympics, winners were given a silver medal and an olive branch, while runners-up received a copper medal and a laurel branch.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] The IOC has retroactively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to the three best-placed athletes in each event to comply with more recent traditions.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] Three ties resulted in athletes sharing medals, increasing the medal count of various nations.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] In addition, five of the bronze medalists at the Games are unknown – two in swimming and three in gymnastics – and several events had no third-place finisher.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] This is the full table of the medal count of the 1896 Summer Olympics, based on the International Olympic Committee (IOC) medal count.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] Some sources, besides the International Olympic Committee (IOC), that display variations in the medal totals, but as the governing body of the Olympic Games, the IOC is considered the most authoritative source for this article.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] These rankings are sorted by the number of gold medals a country earns.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] The number of silver medals is considered next, and then the number of bronze medals.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] If, after the above, countries are still tied, equal ranking is given, and they are listed alphabetically.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] The IOC provides this information; however, the IOC does not recognise or endorse any ranking system.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The **1896 Summer Olympics**, officially known as the **Games of the I Olympiad**, and commonly known as **Athens 1896** (Greek: Αθήνα 1896), were the first international Olympic Games held in modern history.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Organised by the International Olympic Committee (IOC), which had been created by French aristocrat Pierre de Coubertin, the event was held in Athens, Greece, from 6 to 15 April 1896.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Fourteen nations (according to the IOC, though the number is subject to interpretation) and 241 athletes (all males; this number is also disputed) took part in the games.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Participants were all European or living in Europe, with the exception of the United States team, and over 65% of the competing athletes were Greek.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Winners were given a silver medal, while runners-up received a copper medal.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Retroactively, the IOC has designated the top three finishers in each event as gold, silver, and bronze medalists.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the 14 participating nations earned medals.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] On April 6, 1896, American James Connolly became the first Olympic medalist in more than 1,500 years, competing in the triple jump.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals, 11, while host nation Greece won the most medals overall, 47.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The highlight for the Greeks was the marathon victory by their compatriot Spyridon Louis.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The most successful competitor was German wrestler and gymnast Carl Schuhmann, who won four events.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Athens had been chosen to stage the inaugural modern Games during a congress organised by Coubertin in Paris on 23 June 1894, during which the IOC was also created.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The main venue was the Panathenaic Stadium, where athletics and wrestling took place; other venues included the Neo Phaliron Velodrome for cycling and the Zappeion for fencing.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony was held in the Panathenaic Stadium on 6 April, during which most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] After a speech by the president of the organising committee, Crown Prince Constantine, his father officially opened the Games.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras and written by Kostis Palamas.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Olympics were regarded as a great success.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The Games had the largest international participation of any sporting event to that date.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium overflowed with the largest crowd ever to watch a sporting event.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] After the Games, Coubertin and the IOC were petitioned by several prominent figures, including Greece's King George and some of the American competitors in Athens, to hold all the following Games in Athens.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] However, the 1900 Summer Olympics were already planned for Paris, and, with the exception of the Intercalated Games of 1906, the Olympics did not return to Greece until the 2004 Summer Olympics, 108 years later.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] During the 19th century, several small-scale sports festivals across Europe were named after the ancient Olympic Games.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The 1870 Olympics at the Panathenaic stadium, which had been refurbished for the occasion, had an audience of 30,000 people.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Pierre de Coubertin, a French pedagogue and historian, adopted William Penny Brookes's idea to establish a multi-national and multi-sport event (even though the ancient games only allowed male athletes of Greek origin to participate).
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] In 1890, Coubertin wrote an article in *La Revue Athlétique*, which espoused the importance of Much Wenlock, a rural market town in the English county of Shropshire.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] It was here that, in October 1850, the local physician William Penny Brookes founded the Wenlock Olympian Games, a festival of sports and recreations that included athletics and team sports like cricket, football and quoits.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin also took inspiration from earlier Greek games organised under the name of Olympics by businessman and philanthropist Evangelis Zappas in 1859, 1870 and 1875.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Athens Games were funded by the legacies of Zappas and his cousin Konstantinos Zappas and by George Averoff who had been requested by the Greek government to sponsor the second refurbishment of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek government did this despite the cost of refurbishing the stadium in marble already being funded in full by Evangelis Zappas forty years earlier.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] On 18 June 1894, Coubertin organised a congress at the Sorbonne, Paris, to present his plans to representatives of sports societies from 11 countries.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Following his proposal's acceptance by the congress, a date for the first modern Olympic Games was discussed; Coubertin suggested that the Games be held concurrently with the 1900 Universal Exposition of Paris.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Concerned that a six-year waiting period might lessen public interest, congress members opted to hold the inaugural Games in 1896.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] With a date established, members of the congress discussed the selection of a host city.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] It is unknown how Athens was chosen: Coubertin and Demetrius Vikelas's descriptions of the selection process contradicted the congress's official minutes.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Most accounts state that several congressmen first proposed London, but Coubertin dissented.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] After a brief discussion with Vikelas, who represented Greece, Coubertin suggested Athens.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas made the Athens proposal official on 23 June; since Greece had been the original home of the Olympics, the congress unanimously approved the decision.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas was then elected the first president of the newly established International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The return of the Olympic Games to Greece was well-received by the Greek public, media, and royal family.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The Crown Prince conferred their patronage to the games.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] However, the country had financial troubles and was in political turmoil.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The country's prime minister frequently alternated between Charilaos Trikoupis and Theodoros Deligiannis during the last years of the 19th century.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] This instability caused Trikoupis and Stephanos Dragoumis, the president of the Zappas Olympic Committee, which had attempted to organise a series of national Olympiads, to believe that Greece could not host the event.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] In late 1894, the organising committee under Stephanos Skouloudis presented a report that the cost of the Games would be three times higher than originally estimated by Coubertin.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] They concluded the Games could not be held and offered their resignation.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] With the prospect of reviving the Olympic games in doubt, Coubertin and Vikelas commenced a campaign to increase the Olympic movement's popularity.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] On 7 January 1895 Vikelas announced that crown prince Constantine would assume the presidency of the organising committee.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] His first responsibility was to raise the funds necessary to host the Games.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] He relied on the patriotism of the Greek people to motivate them to provide the required finances.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Constantine's enthusiasm increased contributions from the Greek public, raising 330,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,106,157,688 in 2025).
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] A special set of postage stamps was commissioned; the sale of which raised 400,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,340,797,197 in 2025).
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] At the request of Constantine, businessman George Averoff agreed to pay for the restoration of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] As a tribute to his generosity, a statue of Averoff was constructed and unveiled on 5 April 1896 outside the stadium.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC's first regulation, voted on in 1894, was to allow only amateur athletes to participate in the Olympic Games.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The various contests were thus held under amateur regulations, except for fencing matches.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The rules and regulations were not uniform, so the Organising Committee chose among the codes of the various national athletic associations.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The jury, the referees and the game director bore the same names as in antiquity (*Ephor*, *Helanodic* and *Alitarc*).
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George acted as final referee; according to Coubertin, "his presence gave weight and authority to the decisions of the ephors".
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Women could not compete at the 1896 Summer Olympics because Coubertin felt that their inclusion would be "impractical, uninteresting, unaesthetic and incorrect".
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Seven venues were used for the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Panathenaic Stadium was the main venue, hosting four of the nine sports contested.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The town of Marathon hosted the marathon event and the individual road race events.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Fencing was held at the Zappeion, sport shooting at Kallithea, and tennis at the Athens Lawn Tennis Club.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Swimming was held in the Bay of Zea; it was selected because the organizers of the Games wanted to avoid spending money on constructing a special-purpose swimming venue.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Four of the 1896 venues were reused as competition venues for the 2004 Games.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The velodrome would be renovated into a football stadium in the 1960s and was known as Karaiskakis Stadium.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] This venue was renovated in 2003 for use as a football venue for the 2004 Games.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] During the 2004 Games, Panathinaiko Stadium hosted the archery competitions and was the finish line for the athletic marathon event.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The city of Marathon itself served as the starting point for both marathon events during the 2004 Games.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The Zappeion served as the first home of the organizing committee (ATHOC) for the 2004 Games from 1998 to 1999, and served as the press center for non-accredited media during those Games.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] On Easter Monday 6 April (25 March according to the Julian calendar used in Greece until 1923) the games of the First Olympiad were officially opened.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium was filled with between 16,000 and 80,000 spectators, including King George I of Greece, his wife Olga, and other members of the royal family.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras, with words by poet Kostis Palamas.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The first announcements regarding the sporting events to be held featured sports like equestrian and cricket, but these plans were not finalised, and these sports did not make the final program for the Games.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Football is sometimes listed as having been an exhibition or demonstration sport, although whether a football match actually occurred is disputed.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing and sailing events were cancelled on the planned days of competition: sailing due to a lack of special boats in Greece and no foreign entries, and rowing due to poor weather.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Summer Olympics programme featured 9 sports encompassing 10 disciplines and 43 events.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The athletics events had the most international field of any of the sports.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The major highlight was the marathon, held for the first time in international competition.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis, a previously unrecognised water carrier, won the event to become the only Greek athletics champion and a national hero.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Although Greece had been favoured to win the discus and the shot put, the best Greek athletes finished second to American Robert Garrett in both events.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] No world records were set, as few top international competitors had elected to compete and the curves of the track were very tight, making fast times in the running events virtually impossible.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Thomas Burke of the United States won the 100-meter race in 12.0 seconds and the 400-meter race in 54.2 seconds.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Burke was the only one who used the "crouch start" (putting his knee on soil), confusing the jury.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Chile claims one athlete, Luis Subercaseaux, who competed for the nation at the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Subercaseaux's results are not listed in the official report, though that report typically includes only winners and Subercaseaux won no medals.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] He was entered to compete in the 100m, 400m and 800m events but is usually listed as a no show.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] An appraisal of a photo of series 2 of the 100 meters sprint, performed by facial recognition experts of the Chilean forensic police, concluded that Subercaseaux was one of the participants.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The day after the official marathon, Stamata Revithi ran the 40-kilometer course in 5 hours 30 minutes, finishing outside Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Some authors, who believe that "Melpomene" and Revithi are the same person, attribute to the latter the more favorable time of 4+1⁄2 hours.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] She was denied entry into the official race as the 1896 Olympics excluded women from competition.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The cycling competitions used the rules of the International Cycling Association.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The newly built Neo Phaliron Velodrome hosted the track cycling events.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Only one road event was held, a race from Athens to Marathon and back (87 kilometres).
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] In the track events, the best cyclist was Frenchman Paul Masson, who won the one lap time trial, the sprint event, and the 10,000 meters.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] In the 100 kilometres event, Masson entered as a pacemaker for his compatriot Léon Flameng.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Flameng won the event, after a fall and after stopping to wait for his Greek opponent Georgios Kolettis to fix a mechanical problem.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The Austrian fencer Adolf Schmal won the 12-hour race, which was completed by only two cyclists, while the road race event was won by Aristidis Konstantinidis.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The fencing events were held in the Zappeion, which, built with money Evangelis Zappas had given to revive the ancient Olympic Games, had never seen any athletic contests before.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike other sports (in which only amateurs were allowed to take part at the Olympics), professionals were authorised to compete in fencing, though in a separate event.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] These masters professionals were considered gentlemen athletes, just like the amateurs.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Four events were scheduled, but the épée event was cancelled for unknown reasons.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The foil event was won by a Frenchman, Eugène-Henri Gravelotte, who beat his countryman, Henri Callot, in the final.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The other two events were won by Greek fencers: Ioannis Georgiadis won the sabre event, and Leonidas Pyrgos won the masters foil, becoming the first Greek Olympic champion in the modern era.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The gymnastics competition was carried out on the infield of the Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Germany sent an 11-man team, which won five of the eight events, including both team events: in the team event on the horizontal bar, the German team was the only entry.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Three Germans added individual titles: Hermann Weingärtner won the horizontal bar event, Alfred Flatow won the parallel bars, and Carl Schuhmann, who also won the wrestling event, won the vault.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Louis Zutter, a Swiss gymnast, won the pommel horse, while Greeks Ioannis Mitropoulos and Nikolaos Andriakopoulos were victorious in the rings and rope climbing events, respectively.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] A regatta of sailing boats was on the program of the Games of the First Olympiad for 31 March 1896 (Julian calendar).
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The event was cancelled: the official English report blamed a lack of specialty boats had not been provided while the German version also cited a lack of foreign competitors.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing races were scheduled for the next day, 1 April 1896 (Julian).
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Poor weather caused the event to be postponed to 3 pm and German Berthold Küttner stated that he and Adolf Jäger had lined up for the start of the double sculls, the first event to take place.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The event was further postponed to the next day, but the German team still completed the event in the bad weather: they were presented with the winners medal upon the completion of their row.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The next day, the event was formally cancelled when the weather worsened.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee does not recognize Küttner's recollection of the events.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Held at a range at Kallithea, the shooting competition consisted of five events—two using a rifle and three with a pistol.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The first event, the military rifle, was won by Pantelis Karasevdas, the only competitor to hit the target with all of his shots.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The second event, for military pistols, was dominated by two American brothers: John and Sumner Paine.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] They became the first siblings to finish first and second in the same event.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] To avoid embarrassing their hosts, the brothers decided that John would withdraw from the free pistol event.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Sumner Paine won that event, becoming the first relative of an Olympic champion to become Olympic champion himself.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The Paine brothers did not compete in the 25-meter pistol event, as the event judges determined that their weapons were not of the required calibre; Ioannis Phrangoudis won the event.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The final event, the free rifle, could not be completed due to darkness and was finalised the next morning, with Georgios Orphanidis winning the competition.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The swimming competition was held in the open sea because the organizers had refused to spend the money necessary for a specially constructed stadium.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Nearly 20,000 spectators lined the Bay of Zea off the Piraeus coast to watch the events.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The water in the bay was cold, and the competitors suffered during their races.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] There were three open events (men's 100-metre freestyle, men's 500-metre freestyle, and men's 1200 metre freestyle), in addition to a special event open only to Greek sailors, all of which were held on the same day (11 April).
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] For Alfréd Hajós of Hungary, this meant he could only compete in two of the events, as they were held too close together, which made it impossible for him to adequately recuperate.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Nevertheless, he won the two events in which he swam, the 100 and 1200 meter freestyle.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Hajós later became one of only two Olympians to win a medal in both the athletic and artistic competitions, when he won a silver medal for architecture in 1924.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The 500-meter freestyle was won by Austrian swimmer Paul Neumann, who defeated his opponents by more than a minute and a half.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Although tennis was already a major sport by the end of the 19th century, none of the top players turned up for the tournament in Athens.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The competition was held at the courts of the Athens Lawn Tennis Club, and the infield of the velodrome used for the cycling events.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] John Pius Boland, who won the event, had been entered in the competition by a fellow-student of his at Oxford; the Greek, Konstantinos Manos.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] As a member of the Athens Lawn Tennis sub-committee, Manos had been trying, with the assistance of Boland, to recruit competitors for the Athens Games from among the sporting circles of Oxford University.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] In the first round, Boland defeated Friedrich Traun, a promising tennis player from Hamburg, who had been eliminated in the 100-meter sprint competition.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Boland and Traun decided to team up for the doubles event, in which they reached the final and defeated their Greek opponents after losing the first set.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The sport of weightlifting was still young in 1896, and the rules differed from those in use today.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Competitions were held outdoors, in the infield of the main stadium, and there were no weight limits.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The first event was similar in style to what is now known as the "clean and jerk".
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Two competitors stood out: Briton Launceston Elliot and Viggo Jensen of Denmark.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Both of them lifted the same weight, but the jury, with Prince George as the chairman, ruled that Jensen had done so in a better style.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The British delegation, unfamiliar with this tie-breaking rule, lodged a protest.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The lifters were eventually allowed to make further attempts, but neither lifter improved, and Jensen was declared the champion.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Elliot got his revenge in the one hand lift event, which was held immediately after the two-handed one.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Jensen had been slightly injured during his last two-handed attempt and was no match for Elliot, who won the competition easily.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek audience was charmed by the British victor, whom they considered very attractive.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] A curious incident occurred during the weightlifting event: a servant was ordered to remove the weights, which appeared to be a difficult task for him.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George came to his assistance; he picked up the weight and threw it a considerable distance with ease, to the delight of the crowd.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] No weight classes existed for the wrestling competition, held in the Panathenaic Stadium, which meant that there would only be one winner among competitors of all sizes.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The rules used were similar to modern Greco-Roman wrestling, although there was no time limit, and not all leg holds were forbidden (in contrast to current rules).
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Apart from the two Greek contestants, all the competitors had previously been active in other sports.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Weightlifting champion Launceston Elliot faced gymnastics champion Carl Schuhmann.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The latter won and advanced into the final, where he met Georgios Tsitas, who had previously defeated Stephanos Christopoulos.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Darkness forced the final match to be suspended after 40 minutes; it was continued the following day, when Schuhmann needed only fifteen minutes to finish the bout.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] On the morning of Sunday 12 April (or 31 March, according to the Julian calendar then used in Greece), King George organised a banquet for officials and athletes (even though some competitions had not yet been held).
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] During his speech, he made clear that, as far as he was concerned, the Olympics should be held in Athens permanently.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The official closing ceremony was held the following Wednesday after being postponed from Tuesday due to rain.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Again, the royal family attended the ceremony, which was opened by the national anthem of Greece and an ode composed in ancient Greek by George S.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Robertson, a British athlete and scholar.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, the king awarded prizes to the winners.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike today, the first-place winners received a silver medal, an olive branch and a diploma, while runners-up received a copper medal, a laurel branch and a diploma.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Third place winners did not receive a prize.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Some winners also received additional prizes.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis received a cup from Michel Bréal, a friend of Coubertin, who had conceived the marathon event.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Louis then led the medalists on a lap of honour around the stadium, while the Olympic Hymn was played again.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The King then formally announced that the first Olympiad was at an end and left the Stadium, while the band played the Greek national hymn and the crowd cheered.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Like the Greek king, many others supported the idea of holding the next Games in Athens; most of the American competitors signed a letter to the Crown Prince expressing this wish.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin, however, was heavily opposed to this idea, as he envisioned international rotation as one of the cornerstones of the modern Olympics.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] According to his wish, the next Games were held in Paris, although they would be somewhat overshadowed by the concurrent Universal Exposition.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The concept of national teams was not a major part of the Olympic movement until the Intercalated Games 10 years later, though many sources list the nationality of competitors in 1896 and give medal counts.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] There are significant conflicts with regard to which nations competed.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee gives a figure of 14, but does not list them.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Different sources provide differing lists of nations; some exclude countries like Chile and Bulgaria, but the IOC lists competitors from both countries.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Egypt is also sometimes included due to the participation of Dimitrios Kasdaglis; however, the IOC classifies him as a Greek athlete.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Belgium and Russia had entered the names of competitors, but no athletes from these countries competed.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] National Olympic Committees did not yet exist.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the fourteen participating nations earned medals, in addition to two medals won by mixed teams (teams made up of athletes from multiple nations).
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC has retroactively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to the three best placed athletes in each event to comport with more recent traditions.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] In this regard, five of the bronze medalists at the Games are unknown: two in swimming and three in gymnastics.
[src:greece/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals (11), while host nation Greece won the most medals overall (47), as well as the most silver (18) and bronze (19) medals, finishing with one fewer gold medal than the United States.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] The **1906 Intercalated Games** or **1906 Olympic Games** (Greek: Μεσολυμπιάδα, romanized: *Mesolympiada*, lit.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] 'Mesolympics'), held from 22 April 1906 to 2 May 1906, was an international multi-sport event that was celebrated in Athens, Greece.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] It was at the time considered to be part of the series of the Olympic Games, and was referred to as the "Second International Olympic Games in Athens" by the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games is noted for its influence on the Olympic tradition and the records broken during these Games are recorded in history, but are no longer considered part of the Olympic records.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] 894 athletes from 20 nations competed in this competition.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] The idea behind the Intercalated Games was to have an Olympics in Greece every four years, but this would be the first and last.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] The idea was not pursued further, and is sometimes termed the "forgotten Games" in the context of the Olympics.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] The next Olympic Games was the 1908 Summer Olympics in London; the next time the Olympic Games returned to Greece was 98 years later in 2004, also in Athens.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] The Intercalated Olympic Games were to be a series of *International Olympic Games* halfway between what is now known as the Games of the Olympiad, old and new.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] This proposed series of Games, intercalated in the Olympic Games cycle, was always to be held in Athens and was to have equal status with the international Games.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] However, the only such Games was held in 1906.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] One reason for the Games in 1906 was to celebrate the tenth anniversary of the 1896 Games.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] The first Intercalated Games had been scheduled by the International Olympic Committee in 1901 as part of a new schedule, where every four years, in between the internationally organised Games, there would be an Intermediate Games held in Athens.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] This was a compromise; after the successful Games of Athens 1896, the Greeks suggested they could organise the Games every four years.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] Since they had the accommodation and had proven they could hold well-organised Games, they received substantial public support.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] However, Pierre de Coubertin, the founder of the International Olympic Committee, opposed this, as he had intended for the first Games to be in Paris in 1900.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] After Paris had lost the première Olympics, De Coubertin did not want the Games to be permanently hosted elsewhere.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] The 1900 Games were overshadowed by the Exposition Universelle, whose organising committee disagreed with De Coubertin's ideas to such an extent that he resigned.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] The organisation of the 1900 Games was haphazard by today's standards, and although some events, such as archery, drew widespread attention, many others were poorly attended.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] Historians' opinions still differ over which events should be considered "Olympic".
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] Consequently, the IOC supported the Greek idea by granting them a second series of quadrennial Games in between the first series.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] This was a departure from the ancient schedule, but it was expected that, if the ancient Greeks could keep a four-year schedule, the modern Olympic Movement could keep a two-year schedule.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] As 1902 was now too close to be logistically workable, and Greece was experiencing political and economic difficulties, the 2nd Olympic Games in Athens were scheduled for 1906, and the IOC as a whole gave Greece full support for the organisation.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] Louis, Missouri were overshadowed by the Louisiana Purchase Exposition, and their organisation was even worse than that of Paris 1900, while travel difficulties meant that only 20% of the athletes were non-American; of these, half were Canadian.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] It was clear the Olympic Movement was in a dire situation and desperately needed to recapture the spirit of Athens 1896.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] It also needed to do so quickly, as to those who did not participate in St.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] Louis, 1908 was a gap of eight years, by which time there would be little, if any, goodwill left for the Games.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] To make matters worse, Rome, the proposed host for 1908, was also planning an exhibition at the same time as the Games, which had been responsible for the failures of Paris and St.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] To the IOC, the 1906 Athens Games being just around the corner would have been a lifeline.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] While De Coubertin still opposed the idea and did not do anything more than his function required of him, the IOC as a whole gave the Greek organising committee full support for the organisation.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] These games offered Greece the huge opportunity to show that it was important to Europe's present and its past.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] It is clear from the beginning that the Olympic Games 1906 became "a grand project far beyond the status of a mere sports meeting", with new structures built to accommodate the events including the restoration of the ancient stadium in Athens.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games were quite successful: unlike the Games of 1900, 1904 or 1908, they were not stretched out over several months, and unlike 1900 and 1904, they were not overshadowed by an international exposition.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] Their crisp implementation was most likely instrumental in the continued existence of the Games.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] These, along with various other changes, are now accepted as tradition.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] The Games were held from 22 April to 2 May 1906, in Athens, Greece.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] They took place in the Panathenaic Stadium, which had already hosted the 1896 Games and the earlier Zappas Olympics of 1870 and 1875.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] The Games excluded several disciplines that had occurred during the past two Games; it was unclear whether they ought to have been part of the Olympic Games.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] Added to the program were the javelin throw and the pentathlon.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games is noted for its opening and closing ceremonies, which initiated this tradition.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] The 1908 Games introduced the tradition of the host coming in as the last in the parade also.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] These were the first Games to include an opening ceremony with athletes marching into the stadium as national teams behind their flags.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] King George I officially opened the Games.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] Six thousand schoolchildren took part in the first ever Olympic closing ceremony.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] 854 athletes, 848 men and six women, from 20 countries, competed at the 1906 Intercalated Games.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] 78 events in 14 disciplines, comprising 12 sports, were part of the 1906 Games.
[src:greece/1906-intercalated-games] These medals were distributed but are no longer recognized by the International Olympic Committee.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] Parliamentary elections were held in Greece on 3 November 1963.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] The early elections were caused by Karamanlis' resignation.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] It was a fierce confrontation with King Paul I and the royal family that led to the fall of the right-wing government.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] The King (influenced by the Queen Frederika and his son Constantine, according to Karamanlis' later argumentation) didn't follow the prime minister's instructions, concerning an official visit of the royal family to the United Kingdom.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] The King's stance outraged Karamanlis, who submitted immediately his resignation.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] The political unrest was also exacerbated by Georgios Papandreou's fierce opposition.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] The leader of the Center Union was still refusing to accept the official results of the 1961 parliamentary elections, the elections of "violence and fraud", according to his aggressive rhetoric.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] Hence, he refused to legitimise the Parliament and he was inciting public manifestations against Karamanlis and the Palace.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] In his "uncompromising struggle", Papandreou was supported by the United Democratic Left (ΕΔΑ), which was the party that suffered the greatest losses in the 1961 elections and it had reasons to believe, that it was hurt by the alleged election fraud.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] Another incident, which blackened the image of the National Radical Union's government was the killing of the deputy of the United Democratic Left (ΕΔΑ), Grigoris Lambrakis.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] Karamanlis denied any involvement of his government in the killing and he demanded the immediate intervention of the justice.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] Indeed, the resulting investigation by Christos Sartzetakis proved that there was no involvement of the government in the attack.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] Nevertheless, the fact that some far-right fractions were proven to be guilty for the killing harmed Karamanlis, who seemed in the eyes of the public unable to control the extremists.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] After he resigned, Karamanlis demanded immediate elections, wanting to take advantage of the timing.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] Nevertheless, King Paul I preferred to appoint an interim government, led by one of Karamanlis' closest colleagues, Panagiotis Pipinelis, whose role would be to pass a new electoral law, accepted by the main party of the opposition, and to put under control the political unrest.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] Nevertheless, Pipinelis' government failed to present a worthy work and it resigned, under Georgios Papandreou's arrows.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] Then, the King, under the pressure of Papandreou and disregarding Karamanlis' instructions, appointed a new "neutral" interim government, which would carry out the elections.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] This government, fiercefully criticised by Karamanlis, was led by the president of the Court of Cassation.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] Because of the slim difference of votes between the two biggest parties and, also, because of the electoral system, no party managed to have an absolute majority in the Parliament.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] Just after the elections, Karamanlis left for Paris, with his wife.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] Noteworthy, he had also left for France, just after his resignation, but he returned, in order to lead his party in the elections.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] The outcome of the elections consisted a deadlock.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] Constantine Karamanlis proposed the formation of a new interim "neutral" government, whose duty would be to conduct new elections.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] However, Georgios Papandreou was outspoken about his right to form a government of himself, in order to carry out the new elections.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] King Paul I followed Papandreou's instructions, giving him the order to form an interim government, whose role would be to lead the country to new elections.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] Karamanlis questioned the constitutionality of the King's decision, but, instead of insisting in his opinion, he preferred to resign and leave the country.
[src:greece/1963-greek-parliamentary-election] Following his proposal, the party he founded, the National Radical Union chose Panagiotis Kanellopoulos as his successor.
[src:greece/eu] The .eu ccTLD was approved by ICANN on 22 March 2005 and put in the Internet root zone on 2 May 2005.
[src:greece/eu] Even though the EU is not a country (it is a sui generis intergovernmental and supranational organisation), it has an exceptional reservation in ISO 3166.
[src:greece/eu] The Commission and ICANN had extended negotiations lasting more than five years to secure its acceptance.
[src:greece/eu] The sunrise period was broken into two phases.
[src:greece/eu] The first phase, which began on 7 December 2005 was to facilitate applications by registrants with prior rights based on trademarks and geographic names.
[src:greece/eu] The second phase began on 7 February 2006 and covered company, trade and personal names.
[src:greece/eu] In the case of all Sunrise applications, the application needed to be accompanied by documents proving the claim to ownership of a certain right.
[src:greece/eu] The decision was then made by PricewaterhouseCoopers Belgium, which had been chosen as the validation agent by EURid.
[src:greece/eu] On 7 February 2006, the registry was opened for company, trade and personal names.
[src:greece/eu] In the first 15 minutes, there were 27,949 total applications, and after one hour, 71,235.
[src:greece/eu] On 7 April 2006 at 11 am CET registration became possible for non-trademark holders.
[src:greece/eu] Most people requesting domains had asked their registrars to put their requested domains in a queue, ensuring the best chance to register a domain.
[src:greece/eu] This way more than 700,000 domains were registered during the first 4 hours of operation.
[src:greece/eu] Some large registrars like GoDaddy and small registrars like Dotster suffered from long queues and unresponsiveness, allowing people to 'beat the queue' by registering through a registrar that had already processed its queue.
[src:greece/eu] By August 2006, 2 Million .eu domains had been registered.
[src:greece/eu] It was then fourth-largest ccTLD in Europe, after .de, .uk and .nl, and is one of the largest internationally.
[src:greece/eu] The number of .eu domain registrations during the year after the landrush 7 April 2006 to 6 April 2007 seems to have peaked at approximately 2.6 million .eu domains.
[src:greece/eu] The market adjustment that follows a landrush in any domain name extension ensures that the number of registered domains will fall as many speculative domain registrations that failed to be resold will not be renewed.
[src:greece/eu] This is sometimes referred to as the *Junk Dump*.
[src:greece/eu] On the morning of 7 April 2007, the number of active .eu domains stood at 2,590,160 with approximately 15,000 domains having been deleted since 5 April 2007.
[src:greece/eu] Approximately 1.5 million .eu domains were up for renewal in April 2007.
[src:greece/eu] The EURid registry software is based on the DNS.be software and domains are physically renewed at the end of the month of their anniversary of registration.
[src:greece/eu] This process differs from more sophisticated registries like that of .com TLD and other ccTLDs that operate on a daily basis.
[src:greece/eu] As with any post-landrush phase, an extension shrinks as the *Junk Dump* takes effect.
[src:greece/eu] Over one year after the launch of .eu (5 July 2007), the number of .de domains registered was 11,079,557 according to the German .de registry's statistics page, while number of German owned .eu domains according to EURid's statistics page was 796,561.
[src:greece/eu] The number of .uk domains registered was 6,038,732 according to .uk registry Nominet's statistics page.
[src:greece/eu] The number of apparently UK owned .eu domains was 344,584.
[src:greece/eu] The extent of the shrinkage of .eu ccTLD is difficult to estimate because EURid does not publish detailed statistics on the number of new domains registered each day.
[src:greece/eu] Instead it provides only a single figure for the number of active domains.
[src:greece/eu] The number of new registrations are combined with numbers of domains registered.
[src:greece/eu] Approximately 250,000 .eu domains were either deleted or moved into quarantine by 30 April 2007.
[src:greece/eu] In the intervening years the renewal rate has stabilised to approximately 80%, which is above the industry average.
[src:greece/eu] As of November 2019, according to the Tranco rank, the top 100 thousand most popular domains in the world included over 200 .eu domains.
[src:greece/eu] The commission announced on 27 April 2018 that it would like to open registration to all EU and EEA citizens, including those living outside the EU.
[src:greece/eu] The Parliament, the council, and the Commission reached an agreement on this in December 2018, and the corresponding regulation passed the Parliament on 31 January 2019.
[src:greece/eu] The 317,000 British .eu domain names were subject to Brexit negotiations because the .eu domain is reserved for European Union use.
[src:greece/eu] The .eu Brexit would have occurred on 30 March 2020, in case of no deal, but had since been postponed to January 2021.
[src:greece/eu] The UK-EU free trade deal does not cover .eu domains.
[src:greece/eu] The United Kingdom Government released guidance for British citizens regarding .eu domains in October 2020, and .eu holders with a British address attached have been contacted twice by the domain registry regarding their domains – once in October 2020, once in December 2020.
[src:greece/eu] British citizens had their .eu domains suspended on 1 January 2021 for six months, and then withdrawn on 1 July 2021 after a grace period to allow EU/EEA citizens to update the registration information to show their non-UK address.
[src:greece/eu] From 1 January 2022, they were revoked and made available for registration by other entities.
[src:greece/eu] This is the first case of its kind where an institution managing an internet top-level domain has withdrawn domains *en masse* for an entire country.
[src:greece/eu] The second-level domain .europa.eu has been reserved for EU institution sites, with institutions and agencies making the switch from .eu.int to .europa.eu domains on the Europe day of 9 May 2006.
[src:greece/eu] EURid has a rule that the second-level domain name must be in the same script as the top-level domain, so Cyrillic second-level domains must go under .ею instead of .eu, and all domain names under .ею must be spelt using Cyrillic.
[src:greece/eu] Older Cyrillic domains under .eu were cloned into .ею at its launch.
[src:greece/eu] As of March 2024, there are 1,486 registered domains under .ею.
[src:greece/eu] An application for a top-level domain using Greek letters, **.ευ** was submitted in 2016.
[src:greece/eu] The application was originally turned down because it was too visually similar to .eu.
[src:greece/eu] The Greek name of the EU is Ευρωπαϊκή Ένωση (ΕΕ), but .εε would be too visually similar to .ee, the top-level domain of Estonia.
[src:greece/eu] In 2019 steps were taken towards approving .ευ as a domain.
[src:greece/eu] As of March 2024, there are 2,595 registered domains under .ευ.
[src:greece/eu] Domain name speculation, domain name warehousing and cybersquatting are always features of the launch of any new TLD; however, this was more widespread in the case of the .eu launch.
[src:greece/eu] Bob Parsons, CEO and co-founder of GoDaddy, criticized the landrush process designed by EURid.
[src:greece/eu] Particularly, he condemned the use of shell companies by some registrars.
[src:greece/eu] These "phantom" registrars effectively had hundreds of opportunities of registering a domain whereas a genuine registrar effectively only had one opportunity to register the same domain.
[src:greece/eu] Thus some registrants were crowded out of the .eu landrush process and many generic .eu domain names are now owned by the companies using these "phantom" registrars.
[src:greece/eu] Patrik Lindén, spokesman for EURid at the time, denied the allegations by Parsons, stating that "[EURid] verified that each registrar was an individual legal entity.
[src:greece/eu] Each had to sign an agreement with us, and prepay €10,000." Parsons did not dispute that each registrar was a separate legal entity, but noted that creating such entities was trivial: "Mr.
[src:greece/eu] Linden seemed proud that the EURid registry verified that each applicant was a legal entity before it was accredited.
[src:greece/eu] Take a moment and think about what that means.
[src:greece/eu] You can form a "legal entity" for $50 – an LLC – and you are good to go.
[src:greece/eu] While speculative activity occurred with the launch of other domains, it was the scale of the activity that called into question the competence of EURid in protecting the integrity of eu ccTLD.
[src:greece/eu] The EURid organisation investigated some allegations of abuse, and in July 2006 announced the suspension of over 74,000 domain names and that they were suing 400 registrars for breach of contract.
[src:greece/eu] The status of the domains was changed from *active* to *on-hold*.
[src:greece/eu] This meant that the domains could not be moved or have their ownership changed.
[src:greece/eu] The registrars also lost their access to the EURid registration database meaning that they could no longer register .eu domain names.
[src:greece/eu] The legal action relates to the practice of domain name warehousing, whereby large numbers of domain names are registered, often by registrars, with the intention of subsequently selling them on to third parties.
[src:greece/eu] EURid rules state that applications for domains can only be made after a legitimate application has been made to a registrar.
[src:greece/eu] The 74,000 applications were made in the name of only three Cyprus registered companies – Ovidio Ltd., Fausto Ltd. and Gabino Ltd.
[src:greece/eu] The affected registrars, joined in the action by the affected registrants, obtained a provisional order from the Court of First Instance in Brussels, Belgium on 27 September 2006.
[src:greece/eu] The court ordered EURid to release the blocked domain names or else pay a fine of €25,000 per hour for each affected domain name.
[src:greece/eu] EURid complied with the court order and changed the status of the domains from *on-hold* to *active* and restored EURid registration database access to the affected registrars.
[src:greece/gr] Greece applied for the internationalised country code top-level domain (IDN ccTLD) .ελ (.ΕΛ in capital letters) for domain names composed of letters of the Greek alphabet.
[src:greece/gr] This was turned down by ICANN in April 2011 because it was too visually similar to .EA in Latin letters should ICANN ever implement such a TLD (EA is an exceptionally reserved ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 code element for Ceuta & Melilla).
[src:greece/gr] In 2014, ICANN decided to allow Greece to have the domain .ελ.
[src:greece/gr] The right to this top-level domain was handed over to Greece in October 2015, and it became operational on the Internet on 10 July 2018.
[src:greece/gr] For the first three months, domains already held under .gr as they already were in Latin or Greek letters or transcribed into Greek characters could be obtained for .ελ only by the holder of that .gr domain.
[src:greece/gr] Those restrictions ceased to exist in October 2018.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Greece is considered the cradle of Western civilisation and the birthplace of democracy, Western philosophy, Western literature, historiography, political science, major scientific and mathematical principles, theatre, and the Olympic Games.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Ancient Greeks were organised into independent city-states, or *poleis* (singular *polis*), that spanned the Mediterranean and Black seas.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Philip II of Macedon united most of present-day Greece in the fourth century BC, with his son Alexander the Great conquering much of the known ancient world from the Near East to northwestern India.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The subsequent Hellenistic period saw the height of Greek culture and influence in antiquity.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Greece was annexed by Rome in the second century BC and became an integral part of the Roman Empire and its continuation, the Byzantine Empire, where Greek culture and language were dominant.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Greek Orthodox Church helped shape modern Greek identity and transmitted Greek traditions to the wider Orthodox world.
[src:greece/greece-p01] After the Fourth Crusade in 1204, Greece and the rest of the Byzantine empire were fragmented into several Latin and Byzantine successor polities, with most Greek lands finally coming under Ottoman control by the mid-15th century.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Following a protracted war of independence in 1821, Greece emerged as a modern nation state in 1830.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Kingdom of Greece pursued territorial expansion during the Balkan Wars (1912–1913) and World War I (1914–1918), until its defeat in the Greco-Turkish War in 1922.
[src:greece/greece-p01] A short-lived republic was established in 1924 but faced civil strife and the challenge of resettling refugees from Turkey, culminating in a royalist dictatorship in 1936.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Greece endured military occupation during World War II, the subsequent Greek Civil War, and prolonged political instability, leading to a military dictatorship in 1967.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The country began transitioning to democracy in 1974, leading to the current parliamentary republic.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Owing to record economic growth from 1950 to 1973, Greece is a developed country with an advanced high-income economy and a high standard of living.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Shipping and tourism are major economic sectors, with Greece being the ninth most-visited country in the world in 2024.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Greece is part of multiple international organisations and forums, being the tenth member to join what is today the European Union in 1981.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The country's rich historical legacy is reflected partly by its 20 UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The native name of the country in Modern Greek is Ελλάδα (**Elládaⓘ**, pronounced [eˈlaða] ⓘ).
[src:greece/greece-p01] The corresponding form in Ancient Greek and conservative formal Modern Greek (Katharevousa) is Ἑλλάς (*Hellas*, classical: [hel.lás], modern: [eˈlas]).
[src:greece/greece-p01] This is the source of the English alternative name *Hellas*, which is mostly found in archaic or poetic contexts today.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Greek adjectival form ελληνικός (*ellinikos*, [eliniˈkos]) is sometimes also translated as *Hellenic* and is often rendered in this way in the formal names of Greek institutions, as in the official name of the Greek state, the *Hellenic Republic* (Ελληνική Δημοκρατία, [eliniˈci ðimokraˈti.a]).
[src:greece/greece-p01] The English names *Greece* and *Greek* are derived, via the Latin **Graecia** and **Graecus**, from the name of the Graeci (Γραικοί, *Graikoí*), one of the first ancient Greek tribes to settle Magna Graecia in southern Italy.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Apidima Cave in Mani, in southern Greece, has been suggested to contain the oldest remains of early modern humans outside of Africa, dated to 200,000 years ago.
[src:greece/greece-p01] However others suggest the remains represent archaic humans.
[src:greece/greece-p01] All three stages of the Stone Age are represented in Greece, for example in the Franchthi Cave.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Neolithic settlements in Greece, dating from the 7th millennium BC, are the oldest in Europe, as Greece lies on the route by which farming spread from the Near East to Europe.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Greece is home to the first advanced civilisations in Europe and is often considered the birthplace of Western civilisation.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The earliest of them was the Cycladic culture which flourished on the islands of the Aegean Sea, starting around 3200 BC, and produced an abundance of folded-arm and other marble figurines.
[src:greece/greece-p01] 3100 BC to 1100 BC, Crete, a major cultural and economic centre, was home to the Minoan civilisation known for its colourful art, religious figurines, and monumental palaces.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Minoans wrote their undeciphered language using scripts known as Linear A and Cretan hieroglyphs.
[src:greece/greece-p01] On the mainland, the Mycenaean civilisation developed around 1750 BC and lasted until c.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Mycenaeans possessed an advanced military and built large fortifications.
[src:greece/greece-p01] They worshipped many gods and used Linear B to write the earliest attested form of Greek known as Mycenaean Greek.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The collapse of the Mycenaean civilisation ushered in the Greek Dark Ages, from which written records are absent.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The end of the Dark Ages is traditionally dated to 776 BC, the year of the first Olympic Games.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The *Iliad* and the *Odyssey*, the foundational texts of Western literature, are believed to have been composed by Homer in the 7th or 8th centuries BC.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Poetry shaped beliefs to the Olympian gods, but ancient Greek religion had no priestly class or systematic dogmas and encompassed other currents, such as popular cults, like that of Dionysus, mysteries and magic.
[src:greece/greece-p01] At this time, many kingdoms and city-states emerged across the Greek peninsula, some of which went on to establish a number of colonies in Asia Minor, the shores of the Black Sea, and southern Italy (also known as Magna Grecia).
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Greek city-states reached great prosperity that resulted in an unprecedented cultural boom, that of classical Greece, expressed in architecture, drama, science, mathematics and philosophy.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In 508 BC, Cleisthenes instituted the world's first democratic system of government in Athens.
[src:greece/greece-p01] By 500 BC, the Persian Empire controlled the Greek city states in Asia Minor and Macedonia.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Attempts by Greek city-states of Asia Minor to overthrow Persian rule failed, and Persia invaded the states of mainland Greece in 492 BC, but was forced to withdraw after defeat by Athens at the Battle of Marathon in 490 BC.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In response, a number of Greek city-states formed the Hellenic League in 481 BC, led by Sparta, which was the first recorded union of Greek states since the mythical union of the Trojan War.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Greek victories in the Greco-Persian Wars are a pivotal moment in history, as the 50 years of peace afterwards are known as the Golden Age of Athens, a seminal period that laid many foundations of Western civilisation.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Lack of political unity resulted in frequent conflict between Greek states.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The most devastating intra-Greek war was the Peloponnesian War (431–404 BC), which marked the demise of the Athenian Empire and the emergence of Spartan and later Theban hegemony.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Weakened by constant wars among them during the 4th century BC, the Greek *poleis* were subjugated to the rising power of the Argead kingdom of Macedon under king Philip II into an alliance known as the Hellenic League.
[src:greece/greece-p01] After Philip's assassination at Aigai in 336 BC, his son Alexander became king of Macedon and established himself as leader of a Panhellenic campaign against the Persian Empire and abolished it.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Undefeated in battle, he marched to the banks of the Hydaspes, until his untimely death in 323 BC in Babylon.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Alexander's empire fragmented, inaugurating the Hellenistic period.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The newly founded *poleis* of these kingdoms, such as Alexandria and Antioch, were settled by Greeks as members of a ruling minority.
[src:greece/greece-p01] As a result, during the centuries that followed a vernacular form of Greek, known as *koine*, and Greek culture was spread, while the Greeks adopted Eastern deities and cults.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In India, the Indo-Greeks blended Greek and Buddhist religious practices and brought about an artistic renaissance that led to the creation of Greco-Buddhist art.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Greek science, technology, and mathematics reached their peak during the Hellenistic period.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In 280 BC Pyrrhus of Epirus campaigned in Italy against the Romans in order to help Tarentum.
[src:greece/greece-p01] From about 200 BC the Roman Republic became increasingly involved in Greek affairs and engaged in a series of wars with Macedon.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Macedon's defeat at the Battle of Pydna in 168 BC signalled the end of Antigonid power.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In 146 BC, Macedonia was annexed as a province by Rome, and the rest of Greece became a Roman protectorate.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The process was completed in 27 BC, when emperor Augustus annexed the rest of Greece and constituted it as the senatorial province of Achaea.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Despite their military superiority, the Romans admired and became heavily influenced by Greek culture.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Greek-speaking communities of the Hellenised East were instrumental in the spread of Christianity in the 2nd and 3rd centuries, and Christianity's early leaders and writers were mostly Greek-speaking, though not from Greece itself.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The New Testament was written in Greek, and some sections attest to the importance of churches in Greece in early Christianity.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Nevertheless, much of Greece clung to paganism, and ancient Greek religious practices were still in vogue in the late 4th century AD, when they were outlawed by the Roman emperor Theodosius I in 391–392.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The last recorded Olympic games were held in 393, and many temples were destroyed or damaged in the century that followed.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The closure of the Neoplatonic Academy of Athens by Emperor Justinian in 529 is considered the end of antiquity, although there is evidence that the academy continued.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Roman Empire in the east, following the fall of the Western Roman Empire in the 5th century, is known as the Byzantine Empire, but called "Kingdom of the Romans" in its own time.
[src:greece/greece-p01] With its capital in Constantinople, its language and culture were Greek and its religion was predominantly Eastern Orthodox Christian.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Byzantine Greeks self-identified as *Rhōmaîoi* (Ῥωμαῖοι, "Romans", a term which in the Greek language had become synonymous with Christian Greeks).
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Empire's Balkan territories, including Greece, suffered from the dislocation of barbarian invasions; raids by Goths and Huns in the 4th and 5th centuries and the Slavic invasion in the 7th century resulted in a collapse in imperial authority in the Greek peninsula.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The imperial government retained control of only the islands and coastal areas, particularly the populated walled cities such as Athens, Corinth and Thessalonica.
[src:greece/greece-p01] However, the view that Greece underwent decline, fragmentation and depopulation is considered outdated, as cities show institutional continuity and prosperity between the 4th and 6th centuries.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In the early 6th century, Greece had approximately 80 cities according to the Synekdemos chronicle, and the 4th to the 7th century is considered one of high prosperity.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Until the 8th century, almost all of modern Greece was under the jurisdiction of the Holy See of Rome.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Byzantine Emperor Leo III moved the border of the Patriarchate of Constantinople westward and northward in the 8th century.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Byzantine recovery of lost provinces during the Arab–Byzantine wars began in the 8th century.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Most of the Greek peninsula also came under imperial control again.
[src:greece/greece-p01] This process was facilitated by a large influx of Greeks from Sicily and Asia Minor to the Greek peninsula, while many Slavs were captured and resettled in Asia Minor.
[src:greece/greece-p01] During the late 9th, 10th, and early 11th centuries, under the Macedonian dynasty, the empire recovered lost territories and experienced a cultural revival in spheres such as philosophy and the arts.
[src:greece/greece-p01] This period has been dubbed the "Golden Age" of Byzantium.
[src:greece/greece-p01] During the 11th and 12th centuries, under the Komnenos dynasty, the return of stability resulted in the Greek peninsula benefiting from economic growth.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Greek Orthodox Church was instrumental in the spread of Greek ideas to the wider Orthodox world.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Constantinople was captured by the Fourth Crusade in 1204, becoming the capital of the Latin Empire, which briefly ruled much of the former Byzantine lands.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Three Greek rump states–the Despotate of Epirus, the Empire of Nicaea, and the Empire of Trebizond–were established by fleeing Byzantine aristocrats who resisted the Latin rule.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The recapture of Constantinople as the imperial capital in 1261 by the Empire of Nicaea was accompanied by the empire's recovery of much of the Greek peninsula, while the islands remained under Genoese and Venetian control.
[src:greece/greece-p01] During the Paleologi dynasty (1261–1453), a new era of Greek patriotism emerged accompanied by a deliberate embrace of ancient Greek culture.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In the 14th century much of the Greek peninsula was lost by the Byzantine Empire to the Serbs and then the Ottomans.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Constantinople fell to the Ottomans in 1453 and by 1460, the Ottoman conquest of mainland Greece was complete.
[src:greece/greece-p01] During the 15th to early 19th centuries, while much of mainland Greece and the Aegean islands fell under Ottoman control, Venice retained several key territories.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Notably, Crete remained under Venetian rule until 1669, and the Ionian Islands were governed by Venice until 1797.
[src:greece/greece-p01] These islands were subsequently ceded to French and later British control.
[src:greece/greece-p01] While some Greeks in the Ionian islands and Constantinople lived in prosperity, and Greeks of Constantinople (Phanariots) achieved power within the Ottoman administration, much of Greece suffered the economic consequences of Ottoman conquest.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Heavy taxes were enforced, and in later years the Ottoman Empire enacted a policy of creation of hereditary estates, effectively turning the rural Greek populations into serfs, while the Ottoman conquest had cut Greece off from European historical developments.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Greek Orthodox Church and the Ecumenical Patriarchate of Constantinople were considered by the Ottoman governments as the ruling authorities of the entire Orthodox Christian population of the Ottoman Empire, whether ethnically Greek or not.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Although the Ottoman state did not force non-Muslims to convert to Islam, Christians faced discrimination.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Discrimination, particularly when combined with harsh treatment by local Ottoman authorities, led to conversions to Islam, if only superficially.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In the 19th century, many "crypto-Christians" returned to their old religious allegiance.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The nature of Ottoman administration of Greece varied, though it was invariably arbitrary and often harsh.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Some cities had governors appointed by the Sultan, while others, like Athens, were self-governed municipalities.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Mountainous regions in the interior and many islands remained effectively autonomous from the central Ottoman state for centuries.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The 16th and 17th centuries are regarded as a "dark age" in Greek history.
[src:greece/greece-p01] However, prior to the Greek Revolution of 1821, there had been wars which saw Greeks fight against the Ottomans, such as the Greek participation in the Battle of Lepanto in 1571, the Morean War of 1684–1699, and the Russian-instigated Orlov revolt in 1770.
[src:greece/greece-p01] These uprisings were put down by the Ottomans with great bloodshed.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Many Greeks were conscripted as Ottoman subjects to serve in the Ottoman army and especially the navy, while the Ecumenical Patriarchate of Constantinople, responsible for the Orthodox, remained in general loyal to the Empire.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In the 18th century, Greek merchants came to dominate trade within the Ottoman Empire, established communities throughout the Mediterranean, the Balkans, and Europe, and used their wealth to fund educational activities that brought younger generations into contact with Western ideas.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In the 18th century, an increase in learning during the Modern Greek Enlightenment led to the emergence among Westernised Greek-speaking elites of the notion of a Greek nation.
[src:greece/greece-p01] A secret organisation formed in this milieu was the Filiki Eteria, in 1814.
[src:greece/greece-p01] They engaged traditional strata of the Greek Orthodox world in their liberal nationalist cause.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The first revolt began on 6 March 1821 in the Danubian Principalities, but was put down by the Ottomans.
[src:greece/greece-p01] This spurred the Greeks of the Peloponnese and on 17 March the Maniots declared war on the Ottomans.
[src:greece/greece-p01] By October 1821 the Greeks had captured Tripolitsa.
[src:greece/greece-p01] There were revolts in Crete, Macedonia and Central Greece, which were suppressed.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In 1822 and 1824 the Turks and Egyptians ravaged the islands, committing massacres.
[src:greece/greece-p01] This galvanised opinion in western Europe in favour of the Greeks.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Ottoman Sultan Mahmud II negotiated with Mehmet Ali of Egypt, who agreed to send his son Ibrahim Pasha with an army, in return for territorial gain.
[src:greece/greece-p01] By the end of 1825, most of the Peloponnese was under Egyptian control.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Three great powers, France, Russian Empire, and the United Kingdom, each sent a navy.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The allied fleet destroyed the Ottoman–Egyptian fleet at the Battle of Navarino, and the Greeks captured Central Greece by 1828.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The nascent Greek state was recognised under the London Protocol in 1830.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In 1827, Ioannis Kapodistrias, was chosen by the Third National Assembly at Troezen as the first governor of the First Hellenic Republic.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Kapodistrias established state, economic and military institutions.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Tensions appeared between him and local interests and, following his assassination in 1831 and the London Conference of 1832, Britain, France and Russia installed Bavarian Prince Otto von Wittelsbach as monarch.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Otto's reign was despotic, and in its first 11 years of independence Greece was ruled by a Bavarian oligarchy led by Josef Ludwig von Armansperg and, later, by Otto himself, as King and Premier.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Greece remained under the influence of its three protecting great powers.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In 1843 an uprising forced Otto to grant a constitution and representative assembly.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Despite the absolutism of Otto's reign, it proved instrumental in developing institutions which are still the bedrock of Greek administration and education.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Reforms were taken in education, maritime and postal communications, effective civil administration and the legal code.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Historical revisionism took the form of de-Byzantinification and de-Ottomanisation, in favour of promoting Ancient Greek heritage.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The capital was moved from Nafplio, where it had been since 1829, to Athens, then a smaller town.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Church of Greece was established as Greece's national church and 25 March, the day of Annunciation, was chosen as the anniversary of the Greek War of Independence to reinforce the link between Greek identity and Orthodoxy.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Otto was deposed in 1862 because of the Bavarian-dominated government, heavy taxation, and a failed attempt to annex Crete from the Ottomans.
[src:greece/greece-p01] He was replaced by Prince Wilhelm of Denmark, who took the name George I and brought with him the Ionian Islands as a coronation gift from Britain.
[src:greece/greece-p01] A new Constitution in 1864 changed Greece's form of government from constitutional monarchy to the more democratic crowned republic.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In 1875 parliamentary majority as a requirement for government was introduced, curbing the power of the monarchy to appoint minority governments.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Corruption, coupled with increased spending to fund infrastructure like the Corinth Canal, overtaxed the weak economy and forced the declaration of public insolvency in 1893.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Greeks were united, however, in their determination to liberate the Hellenic lands under Ottoman rule; the Cretan Revolt (1866–1869) had raised nationalist fervour.
[src:greece/greece-p01] When war broke out between Russia and the Ottomans in 1877, Greek sentiment rallied to Russia, but Greece was too poor and concerned about British intervention, to enter the war.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Greeks in Crete continued to stage revolts, and in 1897, the Greek government, bowing to popular pressure, declared war on the Ottomans.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In the ensuing Greco-Turkish War of 1897, the badly trained and equipped Greek army was defeated.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Through the intervention of the Great Powers, however, Greece lost little territory, while Crete was established as an autonomous state under Prince George of Greece.
[src:greece/greece-p01] With state coffers empty, fiscal policy came under International Financial Control.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The government, aiming to quell Komitadjis and detach the Slavophone peasants of the region from Bulgarian influence, sponsored a guerrilla campaign in Ottoman-ruled Macedonia, known as the Macedonian Struggle, which ended with the Young Turk Revolution in 1908.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Amidst dissatisfaction with the seeming inertia and unattainability of national aspirations, military officers organised a coup in 1909 and called on Cretan politician Eleftherios Venizelos, who conveyed a vision of national regeneration.
[src:greece/greece-p01] After winning two elections and becoming prime minister in 1910, Venizelos initiated fiscal, social, and constitutional reforms, reorganised the military, made Greece a member of the Balkan League, and led it through the Balkan Wars.
[src:greece/greece-p01] By 1913, Greece's territory and population had doubled, annexing Crete, Epirus, and Macedonia.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The struggle between King Constantine I and charismatic Venizelos over foreign policy on the eve of the First World War dominated politics and divided the country into two opposing groups.
[src:greece/greece-p01] During parts of the war, Greece had two governments: A royalist pro-German one in Athens and a Venizelist pro-Entente one in Thessaloniki.
[src:greece/greece-p01] They united in 1917, when Greece entered the war on the side of the Entente.
[src:greece/greece-p01] After the war, Greece attempted expansion into Asia Minor, a region with a large native Greek population, but was defeated in the Greco-Turkish War (1919–1922), contributing to a flight of Asia Minor Greeks.
[src:greece/greece-p01] These events overlapped with the Greek genocide (1914–22), when Ottoman and Turkish officials contributed to the death of several hundred thousand Asia Minor Greeks, along with similar numbers of Assyrians and a larger number of Armenians.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The resultant Greek exodus from Asia Minor was made permanent, and expanded, in an official population exchange between Greece and Turkey, as part of the Treaty of Lausanne which ended the war.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The following era was marked by instability, as over 1.5 million propertyless Greek refugees from Turkey (some of whom could not speak Greek) had to be integrated into Greek society.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The refugees made a dramatic population boost, as they were more than a quarter of Greece's prior population.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Following the catastrophic events in Asia Minor, the monarchy was abolished via a referendum in 1924 and the Second Hellenic Republic was declared.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In 1935, a royalist general-turned-politician Georgios Kondylis took power after a coup and abolished the republic, holding a rigged referendum, after which King George II was restored to the throne.
[src:greece/greece-p01] An agreement between Prime Minister Ioannis Metaxas and George II followed in 1936, which installed Metaxas as head of a dictatorship known as the 4th of August Regime, inaugurating authoritarian rule that would last until 1974.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Greece remained on good terms with Britain and was not allied with the Axis.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In October 1940, Fascist Italy demanded the surrender of Greece, but it refused, and, in the Greco-Italian War, Greece repelled Italian forces into Albania.
[src:greece/greece-p01] French general Charles de Gaulle praised the fierceness of the Greek resistance, but the country fell to urgently dispatched German forces during the Battle of Greece.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Nazis proceeded to administer Athens and Thessaloniki, while other regions were given to Fascist Italy and Bulgaria.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Over 100,000 civilians died of starvation during the winter of 1941–42, tens of thousands more died because of reprisals by Nazis and collaborators, the economy was ruined, and most Greek Jews (tens of thousands) were deported and murdered in Nazi concentration camps.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Greek Resistance, mainly EAM-ELAS (being the largest organisation) and EDES, was one of the most effective resistance movements in Europe fighting against the Nazis.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The German occupiers committed atrocities, mass executions, and wholesale slaughter of civilians and destruction of towns and villages in reprisals.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Hundreds of villages were systematically torched and almost 1 million Greeks left homeless.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Germans executed around 21,000 Greeks, the Bulgarians 40,000, and the Italians 9,000.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Following liberation, Greece annexed the Dodecanese Islands from Italy and regained Western Thrace from Bulgaria.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The country descended into a civil war between the communist forces and the anti-communist Greek government, which lasted until 1949, with the latter's victory.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The conflict, one of the earliest struggles of the Cold War, resulted in further economic devastation, population displacement and political polarisation for the next thirty years.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Although the post-war period was characterised by social strife and marginalisation of the left, Greece experienced rapid economic growth and recovery, propelled in part by the U.S.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In 1952, Greece joined NATO, reinforcing its membership in the Western Bloc of the Cold War.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The post-war period was dominated by Konstantinos Karamanlis.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Following his appointment as Prime Minister in October 1955, Karamanlis oversaw a period of rapid and sustained economic growth.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Alongside key policymakers such as Georgios Kartalis and Spyros Markezinis, Karamanlis’s government pursued an activist state policy, investing heavily in public infrastructure and industrial development to propel Greece toward the status of a developed nation.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Karamanlis advocated for Greece’s integration into the European Economic Community (EEC) and, in July 1961, Greece signed an agreement to join the bloc.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Centre Union won a minority vote in the 1963 elections and formed a government in the 1964 elections.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Prime Minister George Papandreou's relationship with the new King, Constantine II, deteriorated.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Papandreou openly clashed with the King and resigned in July 1965.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The latter lured in Centre Union members to form unelected coalition governments, resulting in prolonged political instability for the next two years that culminated in a coup in 1967 by a group of colonels led by Georgios Papadopoulos.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Civil rights were suspended, political repression intensified, and human rights abuses, including torture, were rampant.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Economic growth remained rapid before plateauing in 1972.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The brutal suppression of the Athens Polytechnic uprising in 1973 set in motion the fall of the regime, resulting in a counter-coup that established brigadier Dimitrios Ioannidis as the new junta strongman.
[src:greece/greece-p01] On 20 July 1974, Turkey invaded the island of Cyprus in response to a Greek-backed Cypriot coup, triggering a crisis in Greece that led to the regime's collapse and restoration of democracy through Metapolitefsi.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The former prime minister Konstantinos Karamanlis was invited back from self-exile and the first multiparty elections since 1964 were held on the first anniversary of the Polytechnic uprising.
[src:greece/greece-p01] A democratic and republican constitution was promulgated in 1975 following a referendum which chose not to restore the monarchy.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Meanwhile, Andreas Papandreou, George Papandreou's son, founded the Panhellenic Socialist Movement (PASOK) in response to Karamanlis's conservative New Democracy party, with the two political formations dominating government over the next four decades.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Greece became the tenth member of the European Communities in 1981, ushering in sustained growth.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Investments in industrial enterprises and heavy infrastructure, as well as funds from the European Union and growing revenue from tourism, shipping, and a fast-growing service sector raised the standard of living.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In 1981, Andreas Papandreou came to power and implemented an ambitious program of social reforms.
[src:greece/greece-p01] He recognised civil marriage, the dowry was abolished, while expanding access to education and health care.
[src:greece/greece-p01] However, he made controversial foreign policy decisions that fueled the rise of terrorism in Greece.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Papandreou's tenure has been associated with corruption (see Koskotas and Yugoslav corn scandals) and the first constitutional crisis of the new republic, while his economic policies failed to address the persistent stagflation and chronic budget deficits that exacerbated Greece's economic problems.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The country adopted the euro in 2001 and successfully hosted the 2004 Summer Olympic Games in Athens.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In 2010, Greece suffered from the Great Recession and related Eurozone crisis.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Due to the adoption of the euro, Greece could no longer devalue its currency to regain competitiveness.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In the 2012 elections, there was major political change, with new parties emerging from the collapse of the two main parties, PASOK and New Democracy.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In 2015, Alexis Tsipras was elected as prime minister, the first outside the two main parties.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Greek government-debt crisis, and subsequent austerity policies, resulted in social strife.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The crisis ended around 2018, with the end of the bailout mechanisms and return of growth.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Simultaneously, Tsipras, and the leader of North Macedonia, Zoran Zaev, signed the Prespa Agreement, solving the naming dispute that had strained relations and eased the latter's path to EU and NATO membership.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In 2019, Kyriakos Mitsotakis became Greece's new prime minister, after his centre-right New Democracy won the election.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In 2020, Greece's parliament elected a non-partisan candidate, Katerina Sakellaropoulou, as the first female President of Greece.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In February 2024, Greece became the first Orthodox Christian country to recognise same-sex marriage and adoption by same-sex couples.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In 2023, Greece became a member of the Three Seas Initiative.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Located in Southern and Southeast Europe, Greece has the longest coastline on the Mediterranean basin, spanning thousands of islands and nine traditional geographic regions: Macedonia, Central Greece, Peloponnese, Thessaly, Epirus, Aegean Islands, Thrace, Crete and Ionian Islands.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Greece consists of a mountainous, peninsular mainland jutting out into the sea at the southern end of the Balkans, ending at the Peloponnese peninsula (separated from the mainland by the canal of the Isthmus of Corinth) and strategically located at the crossroads of Europe, Asia, and Africa.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Its highly indented coastline and numerous islands give Greece the 11th longest national coastline in the world, with 13,676 km (8,498 mi); its land boundary is 1,160 km (721 mi).
[src:greece/greece-p01] The country lies approximately between latitudes 34° and 42° N, and longitudes 19° and 30° E, with the extreme points being: the village Ormenio in the North and the islands Gavdos (South), Strongyli near Kastellorizo (East), and Othonoi (West).
[src:greece/greece-p01] Gavdos is considered the southernmost point of Europe.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Approximately 80% of Greece consists of mountains or hills, making the country one of the most mountainous in Europe.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Mount Olympus, the mythical abode of the Greek Gods, culminates at Mytikas peak 2,918 metres (9,573 ft), the highest in the country.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Western Greece contains a number of lakes and wetlands and is dominated by the Pindus mountain range.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Pindus, a continuation of the Dinaric Alps, reaches a maximum elevation of 2,637 m (8,652 ft) at Mt.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Smolikas (the second-highest in Greece) and historically has been a significant barrier to east–west travel.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Its extensions cross through the Peloponnese, ending in the island of Crete.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Vikos Gorge, part of the Vikos-Aoos National Park in the Pindus range, is listed by the Guinness book of World Records as the deepest gorge in the world relative to its width.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Another notable formation are the Meteora rock pillars, atop which have been built medieval Greek Orthodox monasteries.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Extensive plains are primarily located in the regions of Thessaly, Central Macedonia, and Thrace.
[src:greece/greece-p01] They constitute key economic regions as they are among the few arable places in the country.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Greece features a vast number of islands—between 1,200 and 6,000, depending on the definition, 227 of which are inhabited.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Crete is the largest and most populous island; Euboea, separated from the mainland by the 60 m-wide Euripus Strait, is the second largest, followed by Lesbos and Rhodes.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The climate of Greece is primarily Mediterranean (Köppen: *Csa*), featuring mild to cool, wet winters and hot, dry summers.
[src:greece/greece-p01] This climate occurs at most of the coastal locations, including Athens, the Cyclades, the Dodecanese, Crete, the Peloponnese, the Ionian Islands, and parts of mainland Greece.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Most of the inland parts of northern Greece, in Central Macedonia, the lower elevations of Western Macedonia and Eastern Macedonia and Thrace feature a humid subtropical climate (Köppen: *Cfa*) with cold, damp winters and hot, moderately dry summers with occasional thunderstorms.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Snowfalls occur every year in the mountains and northern areas, and brief periods of snowy weather are possible even in low-lying southern areas, such as Athens.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Phytogeographically, Greece belongs to the Boreal Kingdom and is shared between the East Mediterranean province of the Mediterranean Region and the Illyrian province of the Circumboreal Region.
[src:greece/greece-p01] It had a 2018 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 6.6/10, ranking it 70th globally out of 172 countries.
[src:greece/greece-p01] In 2024, Greece became the first country in the European Union to ban bottom trawling in marine protected areas what should protect its marine biodiversity.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Rare marine species such as the Mediterranean monk seal and the loggerhead sea turtle live in the seas surrounding mainland Greece, while its dense forests are home to the endangered brown bear, the Eurasian lynx, the roe deer, and more.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The current Constitution, establishing Greece as a parliamentary republic, was enacted in 1975, after the fall of the military dictatorship of 1967–1974, and has been amended four times since.
[src:greece/greece-p01] It consists of 120 articles, provides for a separation of powers into executive, legislative, and judicial branches, and grants extensive specific guarantees (further reinforced in 2001) of civil liberties and social rights.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Legislative powers are exercised by a 300-member unicameral Parliament.
[src:greece/greece-p01] According to the Constitution, executive power is exercised by the Government and the President of the Republic, who is the nominal head of state, is elected by the Parliament for a five-year term and promulgates statutes passed by Parliament.
[src:greece/greece-p01] However, the Constitutional amendment of 1986 rendered the President's office largely ceremonial; the most powerful officeholder is thus the prime minister, Greece's head of government.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The position is filled by the current leader of the political party that can obtain a vote of confidence by the Parliament.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The president of the republic formally appoints the prime minister and, on their recommendation, appoints and dismisses the other members of the Cabinet.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Parliamentary elections are held every four years, but early elections are proclaimed by the President on the cabinet's proposal or if a motion of no confidence passes in Parliament.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Women's suffrage was legislated in 1952.
[src:greece/greece-p01] According to International IDEA's Global State of Democracy (GSoD) Indices and Democracy Tracker, Greece performs in the mid-range on overall democratic measures, with particular strengths in elected government and freedom of movement.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Moreover, according to an OECD report, Greeks display a moderate level of civic participation compared to most other developed countries; voter turnout was 58% during recent elections, lower than the OECD average of 69%.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Since the Kallikratis Programme reform entered into effect in January 2011, Greece has consisted of 13 regions, subdivided into municipalities, of which there are now 332 (there were 325 before the Kleisthenis I Programme came into effect in 2019).
[src:greece/greece-p01] The 54 old prefectures and prefecture-level administrations have been largely retained as *sub-units* of the regions.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Seven decentralised administrations group one to three regions for administrative purposes on a regional basis.
[src:greece/greece-p01] There is one autonomous area, Mount Athos (Greek: *Agio Oros*, "Holy Mountain"), which borders the region of Central Macedonia.
[src:greece/greece-p01] After the restoration of democracy in 1974–1975, the Greek party system was dominated by the liberal-conservative New Democracy (ND) and the social-democratic Panhellenic Socialist Movement (PASOK).
[src:greece/greece-p01] After a repeat election in June 2023, New Democracy gained almost 41% of the popular vote and a parliamentary majority of 158 and its leader, Kyriakos Mitsotakis, who had been Prime Minister from 2019 until the inconclusive election of May 2023, was sworn in for a second four-year term.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Other parties represented in the Hellenic Parliament are the Communist Party of Greece (KKE), Greek Solution, New Left, Spartans, Victory and Course of Freedom.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Foreign policy is conducted through the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and its head, the Minister for Foreign Affairs, currently Giorgos Gerapetritis.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The aims of the Ministry are to represent Greece before other states and international organisations; safeguard the interests of the state and its citizens abroad; promote Greek culture; foster closer relations with the Greek diaspora; and encourage international cooperation.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Greece is described as having a special relationship with Cyprus, Italy, France, Armenia, Australia, Israel, the US and the UK.
[src:greece/greece-p01] There is a long-standing conflict between Turkey and Greece over natural resources in the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Turkey does not recognise a legal continental shelf and exclusive economic zone around the Greek islands.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Due to its geographical proximity to Europe, Asia, the Middle East and Africa, Greece is of geostrategic importance, which it has leveraged to develop a regional policy to promote peace and stability in the Balkans, Mediterranean and the Middle East.
[src:greece/greece-p01] This has accorded the country middle power status.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Greece is a member of numerous international organisations, including the Council of Europe, the European Union, the Union for the Mediterranean, NATO, the Organisation internationale de la francophonie and the UN, of which it is a founding member.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Hellenic Armed Forces are overseen by the Hellenic National Defence General Staff (Greek: Γενικό Επιτελείο Εθνικής Άμυνας – ΓΕΕΘΑ), with civilian authority vested in the Ministry of National Defence.
[src:greece/greece-p01] It consists of three branches: the Hellenic Army (Ellinikos Stratos, ES), the Hellenic Navy (Elliniko Polemiko Navtiko, EPN) and the Hellenic Air Force (Elliniki Polemiki Aeroporia, EPA).
[src:greece/greece-p01] Moreover, Greece maintains the Hellenic Coast Guard for law enforcement at sea, search and rescue, and port operations.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Though it can support the navy during wartime, it resides under the authority of the Ministry of Shipping.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Greek military personnel total 364,050, of whom 142,700 are active and 221,350 are reserve.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Greece ranks 28th in the world in the number of citizens serving in the armed forces.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Mandatory military service is generally one year for 19 to 45 year olds.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Additionally, Greek males between the ages of 18 and 60 who live in strategically sensitive areas may be required to serve part-time in the National Guard.
[src:greece/greece-p01] As a member of NATO, the Greek military participates in exercises and deployments under the auspices of the alliance, although its involvement in NATO missions is minimal.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Greece spends over US$7 billion annually on its military, or 2.3% of GDP, the 24th-highest in the world in absolute terms, the seventh-highest on a per capita basis, and the second-highest in NATO after the United States.
[src:greece/greece-p01] Moreover, Greece is one of only five NATO countries to meet or surpass the minimum defence spending target of 2% of GDP.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The judiciary is independent of the executive and the legislature and comprises three Supreme Courts: the Supreme Civil and Criminal Court of Greece, the Council of State and the Court of Audit.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The judicial system is also composed of civil courts, which judge civil and penal cases and administrative courts, which judge disputes between citizens and the Greek administrative authorities.
[src:greece/greece-p01] The Hellenic Police is the national police force.
[src:greece/greece-p01] It is a large agency with its responsibilities ranging from road traffic control to counter-terrorism.
[src:greece/greece-p01] It was established in 1984, after the merge of the Hellenic Gendarmerie and the Cities Police forces.
[src:greece/greece-p02] As of 2025, the economy was the 54th largest by purchasing power parity (PPP) at $467.590 billion.
[src:greece/greece-p02] In per person income, Greece is 47th in the world at $45,048.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece is the 15th largest economy in the 27‑member European Union.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The economy is advanced and high-income.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece is a developed country with a high standard of living and high ranking in the Human Development Index.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Its economy mainly comprises the service sector (85%) and industry (12%), while agriculture makes up 3%.
[src:greece/greece-p02] In 2021 unemployment stood at 13% and youth unemployment at 33%, compared with respectively 7% and 16% in the EU and eurozone.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece has the largest economy in the Balkans, and an important regional investor.
[src:greece/greece-p02] It has been the number-two foreign investor of capital in Albania and most important trading partner and largest foreign investor in North Macedonia.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The Greek telecommunications company OTE has become a strong investor in other Balkan countries.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece was a founding member of the OECD and the Organisation of the Black Sea Economic Cooperation (BSEC).
[src:greece/greece-p02] In 1979, its accession to the European Communities and the single market was signed, and completed in 1982.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece was accepted into the Economic and Monetary Union of the European Union in June 2000, and in January 2001 adopted the euro as its currency, replacing the Greek drachma.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece is a member of the International Monetary Fund and the World Trade Organisation.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greek economy had fared well (with high growth rates and low public debt) during most of the 20th century; high growth rates were maintained up to the 2008 financial crisis, coupled, however, with high structural deficits.
[src:greece/greece-p02] In 2009, it was revealed deficits had been considerably higher than official figures.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Banks had supplied cash in exchange for future payments by Greece and other Eurozone countries; in turn the liabilities of the countries were "kept off the books", hiding borrowing levels.
[src:greece/greece-p02] This was one of the techniques that enabled Greece to reduce its recorded budget deficit.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The crisis was triggered by the Great Recession, which caused Greece's GDP to contract 2.5% in 2009.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Simultaneously, deficits were revealed to have been allowed to reach 10% and 15% in 2008 and 2009.
[src:greece/greece-p02] This caused Greece's debt-to-GDP ratio to increase to 127%.
[src:greece/greece-p02] As a eurozone member, Greece had no autonomous monetary policy flexibility.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece's borrowing rates increased, causing a crisis of confidence in Greece's ability to pay back loans in early 2010.
[src:greece/greece-p02] To avert a sovereign default, Greece, other eurozone members, and the International Monetary Fund agreed on a €110 billion rescue package in May 2010.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece was required to adopt harsh austerity measures to bring its deficit down.
[src:greece/greece-p02] A second bail-out of €130 billion was agreed in 2012, subject to financial reforms and further austerity.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece achieved a budget surplus in 2013 and returned to growth in 2014.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Partly due to the imposed austerity, Greece experienced a 25% drop in GDP between 2009 and 2015.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The debt ratio, jumped from 127% to about 170%, due to the shrinking economy.
[src:greece/greece-p02] In 2013, the IMF admitted it had underestimated the effects of tax hikes and budget cuts and issued an informal apology.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The policies have been blamed for worsening the crisis, while others stressed the creditors' share in responsibility.
[src:greece/greece-p02] In 2024, the Greek economy was forecast to grow by nearly 3%, approaching its pre-crisis size of 2009 and far outpacing the eurozone's average economic growth of 0.8%.
[src:greece/greece-p02] In March 2026, it was reported that Greece would repay a further €7 billion from its first bailout package ahead of schedule as part of a broader effort to improve its financial standing and reduce debt.
[src:greece/greece-p02] This follows previous earlier repayments to EU creditors, as well as completion of repayment of Greece's loans to the International Monetary Fund two years ahead of schedule in 2022.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The early debt repayments were seen as part of the country's remarkable recovery following the end of the crisis in 2018.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Industrial activity was evident in Greece, since at least the second half of the 19th century (including heavy industry such as shipbuilding), mainly centered in Ermoupolis and Piraeus.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Manufacturing output increased significantly during the period of Greece's rapid economic growth (1950-1973), followed by a sharp decline after 1980 when services, as in other parts of the world, rapidly replaced manufacturing.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The value added by the manufacturing sector as a percentage of GDP in Greece has remained lower than in most European countries (see Table).
[src:greece/greece-p02] In 2025 Greece's main exports were refined petroleum products (26.2%), food products (18.6%), manufactured goods (15.5%), chemicals (13%), and machinery and transport equipment (9.9%).
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece is the European Union's largest producer of cotton and pistachios (7,200 tons in 2021), second in olives (3m tons in 2021), third in figs (8,400 tons in 2022) and watermelons (440,000 tons in 2022) and fourth in almonds (40,000 tons in 2022).
[src:greece/greece-p02] Agriculture contributes 3.8% of GDP and employs 12% of the labour force.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece is a major beneficiary of the EU's Common Agricultural Policy.
[src:greece/greece-p02] As a result of entry to the European Community, much of its agricultural infrastructure has been upgraded and output increased.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Electricity production is dominated by the state-owned Public Power Corporation (known by its acronym ΔΕΗ, transliterated as DEI), which supplied 75% of electricity in 2021.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Some of DEI's output is generated using lignite.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Renewable energy in Greece accounted for 46% of Greece's electricity in 2022, a rise from the 11% in 2011.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Wind power accounts for 22%, solar power 14%, hydropower 9%, and natural gas 38%.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Independent companies' energy production has increased.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece does not have any nuclear power plants.
[src:greece/greece-p02] During the 2nd Nuclear Energy Summit in Paris, Kyriakos Mitsotakis announced that Greece will begin exploring the possibility of using nuclear energy, especially Small Modular Reactors (SMRs), as part of its future energy mix.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The shipping industry has been a key element of economic activity since ancient times.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Shipping remains one of the country's most important industries, accounting for 5% of GDP and employing about 160,000 people (4% of the workforce).
[src:greece/greece-p02] The Greek Merchant Navy is the largest in the world at 18% of global capacity.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The merchant fleet ranks first in tonnage (384 million dwt), 2nd in number of ships (at 4,870), first in tankers and dry bulk carriers, fourth in the number of containers, and fifth in other ships.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The number of ships flying a Greek flag (includes non-Greek fleets) is 1,517, or 5% of the world's tonnage (ranked fifth globally).
[src:greece/greece-p02] Today's fleet is smaller than an all-time high of 5,000 ships in the late 1970s.
[src:greece/greece-p02] During the 1960s, the Greek fleet nearly doubled, through the investment undertaken by the shipping magnates, Aristotle Onassis and Stavros Niarchos.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The modern Greek maritime industry was formed after World War II when Greek shipping businessmen were able to amass surplus ships sold by the U.S. government through the Ship Sales Act of the 1940s.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece has a significant shipbuilding and ship maintenance industry.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The six shipyards around the port of Piraeus are among the largest in Europe.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece has become a leader in the construction and maintenance of luxury yachts.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Tourism has been a key element of the economy and one of the most important sectors, contributing 21% of gross domestic product in 2018.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece was the 9th most visited country in the world in 2022, hosting 28 million visitors, an increase from 18 million tourists in 2007.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Most visitors come from the European continent, while the most from a single nationality are from the United Kingdom, followed by Germany.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The most visited region of Greece is Central Macedonia.
[src:greece/greece-p02] In 2011, Santorini was voted as "The World's Best Island" in *Travel + Leisure*.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Its neighbouring island Mykonos, came in fifth in the European category.
[src:greece/greece-p02] There are 20 UNESCO World Heritage Sites in Greece, and Greece is ranked 17th in the world in total sites.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Twelve further sites are on the tentative list, awaiting nomination.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Since the 1980s, the road and rail network has been modernised.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The Athens Metropolitan Area is served by the privately run Attiki Odos (A6/A62/A621/A64/A65) motorway network and the expanded Athens Metro system, while the Thessaloniki Metro was launched in 2024.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Railway connections play a smaller role than in many other European countries but have been expanded, with new suburban/commuter rail connections, served by Proastiakos around Athens, Thessaloniki, and Patras.
[src:greece/greece-p02] International railway lines connect Greek cities with the rest of Europe, the Balkans and Turkey.
[src:greece/greece-p02] All major islands are served by ferries to the mainland.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Piraeus, the port of Athens, was the third busiest passenger port in Europe as of 2021.
[src:greece/greece-p02] 37 million passengers travelled by boat in Greece in 2019, the second-highest in Europe.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece has 39 active airports, 15 of which serve international destinations.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Athens International Airport served over 28 million passengers in 2023.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Most Greek islands and main cities are connected by air, by the three major airlines, Olympic Air, Aegean Airlines and Sky Express.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Modern digital information and communication networks reach all areas.
[src:greece/greece-p02] There are over 35,000 km (21,748 mi) of fiber optics and an extensive open-wire network.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Broadband internet availability is widespread in Greece: there were a total of 2,252,653 broadband connections as of early 2011, translating to 20% broadband penetration.
[src:greece/greece-p02] In 2017 around 82% of the population used the internet regularly.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Internet cafés that provide net access, office applications and multiplayer gaming are a common sight, while mobile internet on 3G and 4G- LTE cellphone networks and Wi-Fi connections can be found almost everywhere.
[src:greece/greece-p02] As of July 2022, 5G service is accessible in most of major cities.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The UN ranks Greece among the top 30 countries with a highly developed information and communications infrastructure.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The General Secretariat for Research and Technology of the Ministry of Development and Competitiveness is responsible for designing, implementing and supervising national research and technological policy.
[src:greece/greece-p02] In 2017, spending on research and development (R&D) reached an all-time high of €2 billion, equal to 1.1% of GDP.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece was ranked 42nd in the Global Innovation Index in 2025.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece has major technology parks with incubator facilities.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The Hellenic National Space Committee began cooperating with the European Space Agency (ESA) in 1994 and has been its member since 2005.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The country participates in the ESA's telecommunication and technology activities and the Global Monitoring for Environment and Security Initiative.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The National Centre of Scientific Research "Demokritos" was founded in 1959 and is the largest multidisciplinary research centre in Greece.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Its activities cover several fields of science and engineering.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece has one of the highest rates of tertiary enrollment in the world, while Greeks are well represented in academia worldwide; leading Western universities employ a disproportionately high number of Greek faculty.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greek scientific publications have grown significantly in terms of research impact, surpassing both the EU and global average from 2012 to 2016.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Notable Greek scientists of modern times include Georgios Papanikolaou (inventor of the Pap test), mathematician Constantin Carathéodory (known for the Carathéodory theorems and Carathéodory conjecture), astronomer E.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Antoniadi, archaeologists Ioannis Svoronos, Valerios Stais, Spyridon Marinatos, Manolis Andronikos (discovered the tomb of Philip II of Macedon in Vergina), Indologist Dimitrios Galanos, botanist Theodoros G.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Eurostat estimated the Greek population at 10.6 million in 2022.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greek society has changed significantly over recent decades, coinciding with the broader European trend of declining fertility and population aging.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The fertility rate of 1.4 children per woman is well below the replacement rate of 2.1, and one of the lowest in the world, considerably below the high of 5.5 children in 1900.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The crude birth rate in 2023 was 6.8 per 1,000 inhabitants, a significant decline from 8.5 per 1,000 in 2016 and 14.5 in 1981.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece's median age is 44.2 years, the seventh highest in the world.
[src:greece/greece-p02] In 2001, 17% of the population were 65 years old and older, 68% between the ages of 15 and 64 years old, and 15% were 14 years old and younger.
[src:greece/greece-p02] By 2023, those aged 65 and older had risen to 25.4%, while those aged 14 and younger declined to 6.4%; the population aged 15 to 64 rose slightly to 68.2%.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Marriage rates began declining from almost 71 per 1,000 inhabitants in 1981 to 51 in 2004.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Divorce rates have increased from 32.8 per 100 marriages in 2018 to 33.4 in 2022, albeit declining from the peak of 41.2 in 2020.
[src:greece/greece-p02] As a result of these trends, the average household is smaller and older than in previous generations.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The economic crisis exacerbated this development, with 350,000–450,000 Greeks, predominantly young adults, emigrating since 2010, when the population reached its peak of 11.1 million.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Based on current trends, the Greek population is projected to fall to 7.5 million by 2050.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Almost two-thirds of the Greek people live in urban areas.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece's largest and most influential metropolitan centres are Athens (population 3,744,059 according to 2021 census) and Thessaloniki (population 1,092,919 in 2021), that latter commonly referred to as the *symprotévousa* (συμπρωτεύουσα, lit.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Other prominent cities with populations above 100,000 inhabitants include Patras, Heraklion, Larissa, Volos, Rhodes, Ioannina, Agrinio, Chania, and Chalcis.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece is relatively homogeneous in linguistic terms, with a large majority of the native population using Greek as their first or only language.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Among the Greek-speaking population, speakers of the distinctive Pontic dialect came to Greece from Asia Minor after the Greek genocide and constitute a sizeable group.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The Cappadocian dialect came due to the genocide as well, but is endangered and barely spoken.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Indigenous Greek dialects include the archaic Greek spoken by the Sarakatsani, traditionally transhumant mountain shepherds of Greek Macedonia and other parts of Northern Greece.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The Tsakonian language, a distinct Greek language derived from Doric Greek instead of Koine Greek, is still spoken in villages in the southeastern Peloponnese.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The Muslim minority in Thrace, approximately 0.95% of the population, consists of speakers of Turkish, Bulgarian (Pomaks) and Romani.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Romani is spoken by Christian Roma in other parts of the country.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The Council of Europe has estimated that there are approximately 265,000 Romani people living in Greece (2.47% of the population).
[src:greece/greece-p02] Other minority languages have traditionally been spoken by regional population groups in various areas.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Their use decreased radically in the course of the 20th century through assimilation with the Greek-speaking majority.
[src:greece/greece-p02] They are only maintained by the older generations and almost extinct.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The same is true for the Arvanites, an Albanian-speaking group mostly located in rural areas around Athens, and for the Aromanians and Megleno-Romanians whose language is closely related to Romanian and who used to live scattered across areas of mountainous central Greece.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Members of these groups usually identify ethnically as Greek and are bilingual in Greek.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Near the northern Greek borders there are some Slavic–speaking groups, most of whom identify ethnically as Greeks.
[src:greece/greece-p02] It is estimated that after the population exchanges of 1923, Macedonia had 200,000 to 400,000 Slavic speakers.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The Jewish community traditionally spoke Ladino (Judeo-Spanish), today maintained by a few thousand speakers.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Other notable minority languages include Armenian, Georgian, and the Greco-Turkic dialect spoken by the Urums, a community of Caucasus Greeks from the Tsalka region of central Georgia and ethnic Greeks from southeastern Ukraine who arrived in Northern Greece as economic migrants in the 1990s.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Throughout the 20th century, millions of Greeks migrated to the United States, United Kingdom, Australia, Canada, and Germany, creating a large Greek diaspora.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Net migration started to show positive numbers from the 1970s, but until the beginning of the 1990s, the main influx was returning Greek migrants or of Pontic Greeks and others from Russia, Georgia, Turkey the Czech Republic, and elsewhere in the former Soviet Bloc.
[src:greece/greece-p02] A study from the Mediterranean Migration Observatory maintains that the 2001 census recorded 762,191 persons residing in Greece without Greek citizenship, constituting around 7% of the population.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Of the non-citizen residents, 48,560 were EU or European Free Trade Association nationals and 17,426 were Cypriots with privileged status.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The majority came from Eastern European countries: Albania (56%), Bulgaria (5%), and Romania (3%), while migrants from the former Soviet Union (Georgia, Russia, Ukraine, Moldova, etc.) comprised 10% of the total.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The total Albanian national population, which included temporary migrants and undocumented persons, was around 600,000.
[src:greece/greece-p02] 189,000 people of the total population of Albanian citizens were reported in 2008 as ethnic Greeks from Southern Albania, in the irredentist region of Northern Epirus.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The greatest cluster of non-EU immigrant population are in the larger urban centres, especially Athens, with 132,000 immigrants comprising 17% of the local population, and then Thessaloniki, with 27,000 immigrants reaching 7% of the local population.
[src:greece/greece-p02] There is a considerable number of co-ethnics that came from the Greek communities of Albania and former Soviet Union.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece, together with Italy and Spain, is a major entry point for illegal immigrants trying to enter the EU.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Illegal immigrants entering mostly do so from the border with Turkey at the Evros River and the islands of the eastern Aegean across from Turkey.
[src:greece/greece-p02] In 2012, most illegal immigrants came from Afghanistan, followed by Pakistanis and Bangladeshis.
[src:greece/greece-p02] In 2015, arrivals of refugees by sea had increased dramatically due to the Syrian civil war.
[src:greece/greece-p02] There were 856,723 arrivals by sea in Greece, an almost fivefold increase to the same period of 2014, of which the Syrians represented almost 45%.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Most refugees and migrants use Greece as a transit country to Northern Europe.
[src:greece/greece-p02] In July 2025, Greek officials implemented a three month suspension of asylum processing for migrants from North Africa, drawing criticism from human rights groups.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The Greek Constitution recognises Eastern Orthodoxy as the 'prevailing' faith of the country, while guaranteeing freedom of religious belief for all.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The government does not keep statistics on religious groups and censuses do not ask for religious affiliation.
[src:greece/greece-p02] State Department, an estimated 97% of Greek citizens identify themselves as Eastern Orthodox, belonging to the Greek Orthodox Church, which uses the Byzantine rite and the Greek language, the original language of the New Testament.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The administration of the Greek territory is shared between the Church of Greece and the Patriarchate of Constantinople.
[src:greece/greece-p02] In a 2010 Eurostat–Eurobarometer poll, 79% of Greek citizens responded that they "believe there is a God".
[src:greece/greece-p02] According to other sources, 16% of Greeks describe themselves as "very religious", which is the highest among all European countries.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The survey found just 3.5% never attend a church, compared to 5% in Poland and 59% in the Czech Republic.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Estimates of the recognised Muslim minority of Greece, mostly located in Thrace, range around 100,000, about 1% of the population.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Some of the Albanian immigrants to Greece come from a nominally Muslim background, though most are secular.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Following the 1919–1922 Greco-Turkish War and the 1923 Treaty of Lausanne, Greece and Turkey agreed to a population transfer based on cultural and religious identity.
[src:greece/greece-p02] About 500,000 Muslims from Greece, predominantly those defined as Turks, but also Greek Muslims, were exchanged with approximately 1.5 million Greeks from Turkey.
[src:greece/greece-p02] However, many refugees who settled in former Ottoman Muslim villages in Central Macedonia, and were defined as Christian Orthodox Caucasus Greeks, arrived from the former Russian Transcaucasus province of Kars Oblast, after it had been retroceded to Turkey prior to the population exchange.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Judaism has been present in Greece for more than 2,000 years.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The ancient community of Greek Jews is called Romaniotes, while the Sephardi Jews were once a prominent community in Thessaloniki, numbering some 80,000, or more than half of the population, by 1900.
[src:greece/greece-p02] However, after the German occupation of Greece and the Holocaust, it is estimated to number around 5,500 people.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The Roman Catholic community is estimated to be around 250,000 of which 50,000 are Greek citizens.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Their community is nominally separate from the smaller Greek Byzantine Catholic Church, which recognises the primacy of the Pope but maintains the liturgy of the Byzantine Rite.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Old Calendarists account for 500,000 followers.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Protestants, including the Greek Evangelical Church and Free Evangelical Churches, stand at about 30,000.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Other Christian minorities, such as Assemblies of God, International Church of the Foursquare Gospel and various Pentecostal churches of the Greek Synod of Apostolic Church total about 12,000 members.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The independent Free Apostolic Church of Pentecost is the biggest Protestant denomination in Greece with 120 churches.
[src:greece/greece-p02] There are no official statistics about the Free Apostolic Church of Pentecost, but the Orthodox Church estimates the followers as 20,000.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The Jehovah's Witnesses report having 28,874 active members.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Since 2017, Hellenic Polytheism, or Hellenism has been legally recognised as an actively practised religion, with estimates of 2,000 active practitioners and an additional 100,000 "sympathisers".
[src:greece/greece-p02] Hellenism refers to religious movements that continue, revive, or reconstruct ancient Greek religious practices.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greeks have a long tradition of valuing and investing in *paideia* (education), which was upheld as one of the highest societal values in the Greek and Hellenistic world.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The first European institution described as a university was founded in fifth-century Constantinople and continued operating in various incarnations until the city's fall to the Ottomans in 1453.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The University of Constantinople was Christian Europe's first secular institution of higher learning, and by some measures was the world's first university.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Compulsory education in Greece comprises primary schools (Δημοτικό Σχολείο, *Dimotikó Scholeio*) and gymnasium (Γυμνάσιο).
[src:greece/greece-p02] Nursery schools (Παιδικός σταθμός, *Paidikós Stathmós*) are popular but not compulsory.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Kindergartens (Νηπιαγωγείο, *Nipiagogeío*) are compulsory for any child above four.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Children start primary school aged six and remain there for six years.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Attendance at gymnasia starts aged 12 and lasts for three years.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece's post-compulsory secondary education consists of two main school types: unified upper secondary schools (Γενικό Λύκειο, *Genikό Lykeiό*) and technical–vocational schools.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The traditional Technical-Vocational Educational Schools (Τεχνικά και Επαγγελματικά Εκπαιδευτήρια, "TEE") have been replaced by two pathways: Vocational Lyceums (Επαγγελματικό Λύκειο, "EPAL") and Vocational Training Schools (Επαγγελματικές Σχολές, "EPAS").
[src:greece/greece-p02] Public higher education consists of Highest Educational Institutions (Ανώτατα Εκπαιδευτικά Ιδρύματα, "ΑΕΙ") and Schools of Advanced Vocational Training (Σχολές Ανώτερης Επαγγελματικής Κατάρτισης, "SAEK").
[src:greece/greece-p02] The Technological Education Institutions (TEI) have been incorporated into existing universities or merged into new universities.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Students are admitted to public AEI Institutes according to their performance at national level examinations taking place after completion of the third grade of Lykeio.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Students over 22 may be admitted to the Hellenic Open University through a lottery.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The education system provides special kindergartens, primary, and secondary schools for people with special needs or difficulties in learning.
[src:greece/greece-p02] There are specialist gymnasia and high schools offering musical, theological, and physical education.
[src:greece/greece-p02] 72% of adults aged 25–64 have completed upper secondary education, which is slightly less than the OECD average of 74%.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The average Greek pupil scored 458 in reading literacy, maths and science in the OECD's 2015 Programme for International Student Assessment (PISA).
[src:greece/greece-p02] This is lower than the OECD average of 486.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Girls outperformed boys by 15 points, much more than the average OECD gap of 2.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The system is mixed, combining a national health service with social health insurance (SHI).
[src:greece/greece-p02] Per a 2000 World Health Organisation report, its health system ranked 14th in overall performance of 191 countries surveyed.
[src:greece/greece-p02] In a 2013 Save the Children report, Greece was ranked the 19th out of 176 countries for the state of mothers and newborn babies.
[src:greece/greece-p02] As of 2014, there were 124 public hospitals, of which 106 were general hospitals and 18 specialised hospitals, with a total capacity of about 30,000 beds.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Greece's health care expenditures was 9.6% of GDP in 2007.
[src:greece/greece-p02] By 2015, it declined to 8.4%, compared with the EU average of 9.5%.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Nevertheless, the country maintains the highest doctor-to-population ratio of any OECD country and the highest doctor-to-patient ratio in the EU.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Life expectancy is among the highest in the world; life expectancy in 2015 was 81.1 years, slightly above the EU average of 80.6.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The island of Icaria has the highest percentage of nonagenarians in the world; 33% of islanders are 90 or older.
[src:greece/greece-p02] Icaria is subsequently classified as a "Blue Zone", a region where people allegedly live longer than average and have lower rates of cancer, heart disease, or other chronic illnesses.
[src:greece/greece-p02] A 2011, OECD report showed Greece had the largest percentage of adult daily smokers of any of the 34 OECD members.
[src:greece/greece-p02] The obesity rate is 18%, above the OECD average of 15%.
[src:greece/greece-p02] In 2008, infant mortality, with a rate of 3.6 deaths per 1,000 live births, was below the 2007 OECD average of 4.9.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The culture of Greece has evolved, beginning in Mycenaean Greece and continuing into Classical Greece, through the influence of the Roman Empire and its Greek Eastern continuation, the Byzantine Empire.
[src:greece/greece-p03] In ancient times, Greece was the birthplace of Western culture.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Modern democracies owe a debt to Greek beliefs in government by the people, trial by jury, and equality under the law.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The ancient Greeks pioneered in many fields that rely on systematic thought, including logic, biology, geometry, government, geography, medicine, history, philosophy, physics, and mathematics.
[src:greece/greece-p03] They introduced important literary forms as epic and lyrical poetry, history, tragedy, comedy and drama.
[src:greece/greece-p03] In their pursuit of order and proportion, the Greeks created an ideal of beauty that strongly influenced Western art.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Artistic production in Greece began in the prehistoric pre-Greek Cycladic and the Minoan civilisations, both of which were influenced by local traditions and the art of ancient Egypt.
[src:greece/greece-p03] There were interconnected traditions of painting in ancient Greece.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Due to technical differences, they underwent differentiated developments.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Not all painting techniques are equally well represented in the archaeological record.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The most respected form of art, according to Pliny or Pausanias, were individual, mobile paintings on wooden boards, described as panel paintings.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Wall painting in Greece goes back at least to the Minoan and Mycenaean civilisations, with the lavish fresco decoration of sites like Knossos, Tiryns, and Mycenae.
[src:greece/greece-p03] It has been established that ancient Greek sculptures were painted with a variety of colours, a feature known as polychromy.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Art production continued during the Byzantine era.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The most salient feature of this new aesthetic was its "abstract", or anti-naturalistic character.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Classical art was marked by attempts to create representations that mimicked reality, Byzantine art favoured a more symbolic approach.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Byzantine painting concentrated mainly on icons and hagiographies.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Post Byzantine art schools include the Cretan School and Heptanese School.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The first artistic movement in the Greek Kingdom can be considered the Greek academic art of the 19th century (*Munich School*).
[src:greece/greece-p03] Modern Greek painters include Nikolaos Gyzis, Georgios Jakobides, Theodoros Vryzakis, Nikiforos Lytras, Konstantinos Volanakis, Nikos Engonopoulos and Yannis Tsarouchis, while notable sculptors are Pavlos Prosalentis, Ioannis Kossos, Leonidas Drosis, Georgios Bonanos, and Yannoulis Chalepas.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The architecture of ancient Greece was produced by the ancient Greeks (*Hellenes*), whose culture flourished on the Greek mainland, the Aegean Islands and their colonies, from about 900 BC until the 1st century AD, with the earliest remaining architectural works dating from around 600 BC.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The formal vocabulary of ancient Greek architecture, in particular the division of architectural style into three defined orders (the Doric Order, the Ionic Order, and the Corinthian Order), was to have a profound effect on Western architecture.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Byzantine architecture was dominant in the Greek-speaking world and significantly influenced Medieval architecture throughout Europe and the Near East, becoming the primary progenitor of the Renaissance and Ottoman architectural traditions that followed the Byzantine Empire's collapse.
[src:greece/greece-p03] After Greek Independence, modern Greek architects combined traditional Greek and Byzantine elements and motives with Western European movements and styles.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Patras was the first city of the modern Greek state to develop a city plan applying the orthogonal rule by Stamatis Voulgaris, a Greek engineer of the French army, in 1829.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Two special genres can be considered the Cycladic architecture, featuring white-coloured houses, in the Cyclades and the Epirotic architecture in the region of Epirus.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Important is also the influence of the Venetian style in the Ionian Islands and the "Mediterranean style" of Florestano Di Fausto (during the fascist regime) in the Dodecanese islands.
[src:greece/greece-p03] After the establishment of the Greek Kingdom, the architecture of Athens and other cities was mostly influenced by the Neoclassical architecture.
[src:greece/greece-p03] For Athens, the first King of Greece, Otto of Greece, commissioned the architects Stamatios Kleanthis and Eduard Schaubert to design a modern city plan fit for a capital.
[src:greece/greece-p03] After the Great Thessaloniki Fire of 1917, the government ordered for a new city plan under the supervision of Ernest Hébrard.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Other modern Greek architects include Anastasios Metaxas, Lysandros Kaftanzoglou, Panagis Kalkos, Ernst Ziller, Xenophon Paionidis, Dimitris Pikionis, and Georges Candilis.
[src:greece/greece-p03] There is an emerging need to secure the long-term preservation of the archaeological sites and monuments against the growing threats of climate change.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Theatre in its Western form was born in Greece.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Tragedy (late 6th century BC), comedy (486 BC), and the satyr play were the three dramatic genres that emerged in the city-state of Classical Athens and were institutionalised as part of a festival called the Dionysia, which honoured the god Dionysus.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Of the hundreds of tragedies written and performed during the classical age, only a limited number of plays by three authors have survived: Aeschylus, Sophocles, and Euripides.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The surviving plays by Aristophanes are a treasure trove of comic presentation.
[src:greece/greece-p03] During the Byzantine period, theatrical art declined; the only form that survived was folk theatre (*Mimos* and *Pantomimos*), despite the hostility of the state.
[src:greece/greece-p03] During the Ottoman period, the main theatrical folk art was the *Karagiozis*.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The Renaissance, which led to the modern Greek theatre, took place in the Venetian Crete.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Significant dramatists of the era include Vitsentzos Kornaros and Georgios Chortatzis.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Modern Greek theatre was born after independence, in the early 19th century, and initially was influenced by Heptanesean theatre and melodrama, such as the Italian opera.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The Nobile Teatro di San Giacomo di Corfù was the first theatre and opera house of modern Greece and the place where the first Greek opera, Spyridon Xyndas' *The Parliamentary Candidate* was performed.
[src:greece/greece-p03] During the late 19th and early 20th century, the Athenian theatre scene was dominated by revues, musical comedies, operettas and nocturnes and notable playwrights included Spyridon Samaras, Dionysios Lavrangas, Theophrastos Sakellaridis.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The National Theatre of Greece was opened in 1900 as *Royal Theatre*.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Significant directors include Dimitris Rontiris, Alexis Minotis, and Karolos Koun.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Greek literature can be divided into three main categories: Ancient, Byzantine, and modern Greek.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Athens is considered the birthplace of Western literature.
[src:greece/greece-p03] At the beginning of Greek literature stand the monumental works of Homer: the *Iliad* and the *Odyssey*, composed around 800 BC or after.
[src:greece/greece-p03] In the classical period, many of the genres of Western literature became more prominent.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Lyrical poetry, odes, pastorals, elegies, epigrams; dramatic presentations of comedy and tragedy; historiography, rhetorical treatises, philosophical dialectics, and philosophical treatises all arose in this period.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The two major lyrical poets were Sappho and Pindar.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Herodotus and Thucydides are two of the most influential historians in this period.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Byzantine literature written in Attic, Medieval and early Modern Greek, is the expression of the intellectual life of the Byzantine Greeks during the Christian Middle Ages.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Although *popular* Byzantine literature and early Modern Greek literature both began in the 11th century, the two are indistinguishable.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Modern Greek literature refers to literature written in the common Modern Greek language, emerging in the late Byzantine period of the 11th century.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The Cretan Renaissance poem *Erotokritos* is considered the masterpiece of this period.
[src:greece/greece-p03] It is a verse romance written around 1600 by Vitsentzos Kornaros (1553–1613).
[src:greece/greece-p03] Later, during the period of Greek enlightenment (Diafotismos), writers such as Adamantios Korais and Rigas Feraios prepared with their works the Greek Revolution.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Two Greek authors have been awarded the Nobel Prize in Literature: George Seferis in 1963, and Odysseas Elytis in 1979.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Ancient Greek philosophy involved a disposition to value reasoning and thinking critically of traditional culture, thus inaugurating the Western intellectual tradition.
[src:greece/greece-p03] While thinkers before him provided proto-scientific explanations of the natural world, Socrates in 5th-century Athens systematically enquired ethics; the next century, his disciple, Plato, wrote presently still pertinent dialogues about ethics, politics, metaphysics, and epistemology.
[src:greece/greece-p03] There were also topics of treatises composed by Plato's prolific student, Aristotle, whose thought, especially in physics, infused the West for centuries.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Other philosophical schools emerged during the Hellenistic period, Cynicism, Stoicism, Epicureanism and Skepticism, while Neoplatonism dominated subsequent thought.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Byzantine philosophy was characterised by a Christian world-view, but one which could draw ideas directly from the Greek texts of Plato, Aristotle, and the Neoplatonists.
[src:greece/greece-p03] On the eve of the Fall of Constantinople, Gemistus Pletho tried to restore the use of the term "Hellene" and advocated the return to the Olympian Gods of the ancient world.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Byzantine Greek scholars, who were largely responsible for preserving Classical Greek knowledge, fled to the West after the fall of Byzantium, taking with them literature and significantly contributing to the Renaissance.
[src:greece/greece-p03] In the modern period, Diafotismos (Greek: Διαφωτισμός, "enlightenment", "illumination") was the Greek expression of the Age of Enlightenment and its philosophical and political ideas.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Notable representatives were Adamantios Korais, Rigas Feraios and Theophilos Kairis.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Other modern era Greek philosophers or political scientists include Helle Lambridis, Cornelius Castoriadis, Nicos Poulantzas and Christos Yannaras.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Greek vocal music dates back to ancient times, when mixed-gender choruses performed for entertainment, celebration, and spiritual reasons.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Instruments included the double-reed aulos and the plucked string instrument, the lyre, especially the special kind called a kithara.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Music played an important role in education.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Boys were taught music from the age of six.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Later influences from the Roman Empire, the Middle East, and the Byzantine Empire affected Greek music.
[src:greece/greece-p03] While the new technique of polyphony was developing in the West, the Eastern Orthodox Church resisted change.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Therefore, Byzantine music remained monophonic and without any form of instrumental accompaniment.
[src:greece/greece-p03] As a result, and despite certain attempts by certain Greek chanters, Byzantine music was deprived of elements which, in the West, encouraged an unimpeded development of art.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Byzantium presented the monophonic Byzantine chant, a melodic music, with rhythmical variety and expressive power.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Along with Byzantine chant and music, the Greeks cultivated the Greek folk song (*Demotiko*), which is divided into two cycles, the akritic and klephtic.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The akritic was created between the 9th and 10th centuries and depicted the life and struggles of the akrites (frontier guards) of the Byzantine Empire, the most well-known of whom was Digenes Akritas.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The klephtic cycle came into being between the late Byzantine period and the start of the Greek War of Independence.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The most famous klephtic and modern Greek folk song is *The Battle of Mount Olympus and Mount Kisavos*, a ballad based on a musico-poetic motif dating back to classical Greece.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The klephtic cycle, together with historical songs, *paraloghes* (narrative song or ballad), love songs, mantinades, wedding songs, songs of exile, and dirges express the life of the Greeks.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The Heptanesean kantádhes (καντάδες 'serenades'; sing.: καντάδα) became the forerunners of the Greek modern urban popular song, influencing its development.
[src:greece/greece-p03] For the first part of the next century, Greek composers continued to borrow elements from the Heptanesean style.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The most successful songs during 1870–1930 were the so-called Athenian serenades, and the songs performed on stage ('theatrical revue songs') in revues, operettas, and nocturnes that dominated Athens' theatre scene.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Rebetiko, initially a music associated with the lower classes, later gained greater acceptance as the rough edges of its overt subcultural character were softened, sometimes to the point of unrecognisability.
[src:greece/greece-p03] It was the base of the later laïkó (song of the people).
[src:greece/greece-p03] The leading performers of the genre include Vassilis Tsitsanis, Grigoris Bithikotsis, Stelios Kazantzidis, George Dalaras, Haris Alexiou and Glykeria.
[src:greece/greece-p03] It was through the Ionian islands (which were under western rule) that major advances of the western European classical music were introduced to mainland Greeks.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The region is notable for the birth of the first school of modern Greek classical music (Heptanesean or Ionian School), established in 1815.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Prominent representatives of this genre include Nikolaos Mantzaros, Spyridon Xyndas, Spyridon Samaras and Pavlos Carrer.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Manolis Kalomiris is considered the founder of the Greek National School of Music.
[src:greece/greece-p03] In the 20th century, Greek composers had a significant impact on the development of avant garde and modern classical music, with figures such as Iannis Xenakis, Nikos Skalkottas, and Dimitri Mitropoulos achieving international prominence.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Greek American composers known for their film scores include Yanni and Basil Poledouris.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Greek opera singers and classical musicians of the 20th and 21st century include Maria Callas, Nana Mouskouri, Mario Frangoulis, Leonidas Kavakos, and Dimitris Sgouros.
[src:greece/greece-p03] During the Greek junta of 1967–74, the music of Mikis Theodorakis was banned, the composer jailed, internally exiled, and put in a concentration camp, before finally being allowed to leave Greece due to international reaction.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Released during the junta years, *Make Love, Stop the Gunfire*, by pop group Poll is considered the first anti-war protest song in Greek rock.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Greece participated in the Eurovision Song Contest 35 times after its debut at the 1974 Contest.
[src:greece/greece-p03] In 2005, Greece won with "My Number One", performed by Greek-Swedish singer Elena Paparizou, which became a smash hit in different countries and especially in Greece, and the 51st Eurovision Song Contest of 2006 was held in Athens.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Cinema first appeared in Greece in 1896, but the first cine-theatre was opened in 1907 in Athens.
[src:greece/greece-p03] In 1914, the *Asty Films Company* was founded and the production of long films began.
[src:greece/greece-p03] *Golfo*, a well known traditional love story, is considered the first Greek feature film, although there were minor productions such as newscasts before.
[src:greece/greece-p03] In 1931, Orestis Laskos directed *Daphnis and Chloe*, containing one of the first nude scene in European cinema; it was the first Greek movie played abroad.
[src:greece/greece-p03] In 1944, Katina Paxinou was honoured with the Best Supporting Actress Academy Award for *For Whom the Bell Tolls*.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The 1950s and early 1960s are considered to be a "golden age" of Greek cinema.
[src:greece/greece-p03] More than sixty films per year were made, with most having film noir elements.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Cacoyannis directed *Zorba the Greek* with Anthony Quinn which received Best Director, Best Adapted Screenplay, and Best Film nominations.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Finos Film contributed in this period with movies such as *Λατέρνα, Φτώχεια και Φιλότιμο*, *Madalena*, *I theia ap' to Chicago*, *Το ξύλο βγήκε από τον Παράδεισο* and many more.
[src:greece/greece-p03] During the 1970s and 1980s, Theo Angelopoulos directed notable movies.
[src:greece/greece-p03] His film *Eternity and a Day* won the Palme d'Or and the Prize of the Ecumenical Jury at the 1998 Cannes Film Festival.
[src:greece/greece-p03] There are internationally renowned filmmakers in the Greek diaspora, such as the Greek-French Costa-Gavras and the Greek-Americans Elia Kazan, John Cassavetes, and Alexander Payne.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Yorgos Lanthimos has received four Academy Award nominations for his work, including Best Foreign Language Film for *Dogtooth* (2009), Best Original Screenplay for *The Lobster* (2015), and Best Picture and Best Director for *The Favourite* (2018).
[src:greece/greece-p03] Greek cuisine is characteristic of the Mediterranean diet, which is epitomised by dishes of Crete.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Greek cuisine incorporates fresh ingredients into local dishes such as moussaka, pastitsio, classic Greek salad, fasolada, spanakopita and souvlaki.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Some dishes can be traced back to ancient Greece like skordalia (a thick purée of walnuts, almonds, crushed garlic and olive oil), lentil soup, retsina (white or rosé wine sealed with pine resin) and pasteli (candy bar with sesame seeds baked with honey).
[src:greece/greece-p03] People often enjoy eating from small dishes such as meze with dips such as tzatziki, grilled octopus and small fish, feta cheese, dolmades (rice, currants and pine kernels wrapped in vine leaves), various pulses, olives and cheese.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Sweet desserts include melomakarona, diples and galaktoboureko, and drinks such as ouzo, metaxa and wines including retsina.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Greek cuisine differs from different parts of the mainland and island to island.
[src:greece/greece-p03] It uses some flavourings more often than other Mediterranean cuisines: oregano, mint, garlic, onion, dill and bay laurel leaves.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Other common herbs and spices include basil, thyme and fennel seed.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Many recipes, especially in the northern parts of the country, use "sweet" spices in combination with meat, for example cinnamon and cloves in stews.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Koutoukia are an underground restaurant common in Greece.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Greece is the birthplace of the ancient Olympic Games, first recorded in 776 BC in Olympia, and hosted the modern Olympic Games twice, the inaugural 1896 Summer Olympics and the 2004 Summer Olympics.
[src:greece/greece-p03] During the parade of nations, Greece is always called first, as the founding nation of the ancient precursor of the modern Olympics.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The nation has competed at every Summer Olympic Games, one of only four countries to have done so.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Having won a total of 129 medals (36 gold, 46 silver and 47 bronze), Greece is ranked 35th by gold medals in the all-time Summer Olympic medal count.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Their best ever performance was in the 1896 Summer Olympics, when Greece finished second in the medal table with 10 gold medals.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The Greece national football team, ranked 47th in the world as of 2024 (and having reached a high of 8th in 2008 and 2011), were crowned European Champions in Euro 2004 in one of the biggest upsets in the history of the sport.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The Greek Super League is the highest professional football league, comprising fourteen teams.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The most successful are Olympiacos, Panathinaikos, and AEK Athens.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The Greek national basketball team has a decades-long tradition of excellence and is considered among the world's top basketball powers.
[src:greece/greece-p03] As of 2026, it ranked 12th in the world and 7th in Europe.
[src:greece/greece-p03] They have won the European Championship twice in 1987 and 2005, and have reached the final four in two of the last four FIBA World Championships, taking the second place in the world in 2006 FIBA World Championship.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The domestic top basketball league, A1 Ethniki, has fourteen teams.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The most successful Greek teams are Panathinaikos, Olympiacos, Aris Thessaloniki, AEK Athens and PAOK.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Greek basketball teams are the most successful in European basketball the last 25 years.
[src:greece/greece-p03] After the 2005 European Championship triumph of the Greek national basketball team, Greece became the reigning European Champion in both football and basketball.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The Greece women's national water polo team have emerged as one of the leading powers in the world, becoming World Champions in 2011.
[src:greece/greece-p03] They won gold at the 2005 World League and silver at the 2010 and 2012 European Championships.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The Greece men's national water polo team became the third best water polo team in the world in 2005.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The domestic top water polo leagues, Greek Men's Water Polo League and Greek Women's Water Polo League are considered amongst the top national leagues in European water polo, as its clubs have made significant success in European competitions.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The Greek men's national volleyball team has won two bronze medals, one in the European Volleyball Championship and another one in the Men's European Volleyball League and a 5th place in the Olympic Games.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The Greek league, the A1 Ethniki, is considered one of the top volleyball leagues in Europe and Greek clubs have had significant success in European competitions.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Olympiacos is the most successful volleyball club in the country.
[src:greece/greece-p03] In handball, AC Diomidis Argous is the only Greek club to have won a European Cup.
[src:greece/greece-p03] According to Greek law, every Sunday of the year is a public holiday.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Since the late '70s, Saturday has also been a non-school and non-working day.
[src:greece/greece-p03] In addition, there are four mandatory official public holidays: 25 March (*Greek Independence Day*), Easter Monday, 15 August (*Assumption or Dormition of the Holy Virgin*), and 25 December (*Christmas*).
[src:greece/greece-p03] 1 May (*Labour Day*) and 28 October (*Ohi Day*) are regulated by law as being optional but it is customary for employees to be given the day off.
[src:greece/greece-p03] There are, however, more public holidays celebrated in Greece than announced by the Ministry of Labour each year as either obligatory or optional.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The list of these non-fixed national holidays rarely changes and has not changed in recent decades, giving a total of eleven national holidays each year.
[src:greece/greece-p03] In addition to the national holidays, there are public holidays that are not celebrated nationwide, but only by a specific professional group or a local community.
[src:greece/greece-p03] For example, many municipalities have a "Patron Saint" parallel to "Name Days", or a "Liberation Day".
[src:greece/greece-p03] On such days it is customary for schools to take the day off.
[src:greece/greece-p03] Notable festivals, beyond the religious feasts, include Patras Carnival, Athens Festival, and local wine festivals.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The city of Thessaloniki is also home of a number of festivals and events.
[src:greece/greece-p03] The Thessaloniki International Film Festival is one of the most important film festivals in Southern Europe.
